00:45:40,671 --> 00:45:42,940
This team finished first.

1206
00:45:44,108 --> 00:45:45,943
IT'S OVER?

1207
00:45:46,009 --> 00:45:46,844
Go ring the bell.

1208
00:45:46,910 --> 00:45:48,579
-Sam didn't ring the bell.
-We didn't ring it?

1209
00:45:48,645 --> 00:45:50,414
He even makes Sam ring the bell.

1210
00:45:50,481 --> 00:45:52,116
THE ATTENTION HUNTERS ARE DONE TOO

1211
00:45:52,182 --> 00:45:53,884
They're now done too.

1212
00:45:53,951 --> 00:45:55,486
Both teams are done cooking!

1213
00:45:55,552 --> 00:45:57,688
A TABLE FULL OF MIYEOK

1214
00:45:57,755 --> 00:45:58,722
Those look great.

1215
00:45:59,890 --> 00:46:00,891
Whoa.

1216
00:46:01,825 --> 00:46:03,360
These look so good.

1217
00:46:03,427 --> 00:46:05,596
-It looks great.
-They really did it in 15 minutes.

1218
00:46:06,730 --> 00:46:08,398
TRULY AMAZED

1219
00:46:09,767 --> 00:46:12,202
All <i>miyeok</i> dishes

1220
00:46:12,269 --> 00:46:15,105
for Director Kang are finished.

1221
00:46:15,172 --> 00:46:17,508
-Great work, four chefs.
-Yes.

1222
00:46:17,574 --> 00:46:18,609
Great work.

1223
00:46:19,643 --> 00:46:22,412
Any thoughts on the cook-off,
Director Kang?

1224
00:46:22,479 --> 00:46:24,448
You were all so cool.

1225
00:46:24,515 --> 00:46:25,449
HARD AGREE

1226
00:46:25,516 --> 00:46:27,651
Thank you so much.
And these look delicious.

1227
00:46:27,718 --> 00:46:29,453
It already smells great.

1228
00:46:29,520 --> 00:46:30,587
I'm dying to try these.

1229
00:46:30,654 --> 00:46:32,422
Here's one thing I noticed in the kitchen.

1230
00:46:32,489 --> 00:46:35,592
-Ho-young orders Sam around a lot.
-It seemed like it.

1231
00:46:35,659 --> 00:46:37,227
As they were wrapping up, he said,

1232
00:46:37,294 --> 00:46:38,762
"Run over and at least ring the bell."

1233
00:46:38,829 --> 00:46:40,664
HE DID MAKE HIM DO IT

1234
00:46:40,731 --> 00:46:44,201
Even I got scared.
Sam looked flustered and then moved.

1235
00:46:44,268 --> 00:46:45,569
COPYING THAT SOMEONE?

1236
00:46:45,636 --> 00:46:47,638
Ho-young, you order him around too much.

1237
00:46:47,704 --> 00:46:50,641
Hyun-suk and Poong finished cooking first,

1238
00:46:50,707 --> 00:46:53,510
<i>so please try BMB first.</i>

1239
00:46:53,577 --> 00:46:55,546
SMOOTHLY BLENDED MIYEOK SAUCE
AND SOFT CRAB CAKE

1240
00:46:55,746 --> 00:46:59,917
CHERRY ON TOP WITH RAMYEON FLAVORED BUGAK
AND MIYEOK GAT

1241
00:47:00,350 --> 00:47:03,921
TEAM CHOI HYUN-SUK & KIM POONG,
BMB BY THE STAR HUNTERS

1242
00:47:03,987 --> 00:47:05,122
Gosh.

1243
00:47:05,189 --> 00:47:06,590
That looks so good.

1244
00:47:06,657 --> 00:47:09,326
The presentation is extraordinary.

1245
00:47:09,393 --> 00:47:12,596
If you take a closer look,

1246
00:47:12,663 --> 00:47:17,301
you'll be reminded of a character
from <i>KPop Demon Hunters.</i>

1247
00:47:17,367 --> 00:47:18,435
Huh? Which one?

1248
00:47:18,502 --> 00:47:19,369
The <i>gat?</i>

1249
00:47:19,436 --> 00:47:20,437
Jinu?

1250
00:47:20,504 --> 00:47:21,772
Gwi-Ma.

1251
00:47:23,140 --> 00:47:24,875
IN THE SHAPE OF GWI-MA OF KDH?

1252
00:47:24,942 --> 00:47:28,645
I made flames
with <i>ramyeon</i> soup base and seaweed.

1253
00:47:28,712 --> 00:47:30,380
It's actually Gwi-Ma.

1254
00:47:30,447 --> 00:47:32,916
-That's why it's red.
-I see.

1255
00:47:32,983 --> 00:47:35,285
She seems to understand
after hearing the explanation.

1256
00:47:35,352 --> 00:47:37,020
How should she eat this?

1257
00:47:37,087 --> 00:47:39,156
Scoop up everything you see.

1258
00:47:39,223 --> 00:47:42,092
Not only will you taste
the crab cake and <i>miyeok</i>,

1259
00:47:42,159 --> 00:47:44,595
but you'll also get
the crispy texture at the end.

1260
00:47:44,661 --> 00:47:45,863
Okay.

1261
00:47:45,929 --> 00:47:47,831
-I wonder how she'll like it.
-It looks so good.

1262
00:47:48,599 --> 00:47:52,369
-It looks very crunchy.
-You should eat it with lots of sauce.

1263
00:47:53,370 --> 00:47:55,072
-It's…
-Mmm.

1264
00:47:55,138 --> 00:47:58,175
The seaweed sauce was really nice
when I tasted it.

1265
00:47:58,242 --> 00:48:00,944
-The blended seaweed becomes a sauce.
-Yes.

1266
00:48:01,311 --> 00:48:02,746
YUM

1267
00:48:04,281 --> 00:48:06,917
I wonder if she'll like it.

1268
00:48:06,984 --> 00:48:08,785
She lived many years in America, so…

1269
00:48:08,852 --> 00:48:11,088
It's quite creamy and delicious.

1270
00:48:11,755 --> 00:48:13,190
It's creamy?

1271
00:48:13,257 --> 00:48:15,425
-And the fritter is really crispy.
-It is?

1272
00:48:15,492 --> 00:48:19,963
-I can also taste the <i>ramyeon</i> soup base.
-You can?

1273
00:48:20,030 --> 00:48:23,300
Poong was in charge of those fritters.

1274
00:48:23,367 --> 00:48:26,770
Also, the crab meat was cooked perfectly.

1275
00:48:26,837 --> 00:48:28,906
-The crab meat? Crab cake <i>jeon</i>.
-Yes.

1276
00:48:29,473 --> 00:48:30,574
ANOTHER BITE OF CRAB CAKE

1277
00:48:30,641 --> 00:48:32,109
She loves crab meat.

1278
00:48:32,175 --> 00:48:33,977
Does the <i>miyeok</i> play a part?

1279
00:48:34,044 --> 00:48:35,712
Yes, very much.

1280
00:48:35,779 --> 00:48:39,216
It's a part of every aspect of the dish.

1281
00:48:39,283 --> 00:48:41,318
I can definitely call this a <i>miyeok</i> dish.

1282
00:48:41,919 --> 00:48:43,287
I'm sorry, but is that the shell?

1283
00:48:43,353 --> 00:48:45,222
-Yes, it is.
-Oh, no.

1284
00:48:45,289 --> 00:48:47,858
-She found a piece of crab shell.
-Crab shell?

1285
00:48:47,925 --> 00:48:49,493
Congratulations!

1286
00:48:49,559 --> 00:48:51,461
You have won a dining voucher to CHOI Dot.

1287
00:48:51,528 --> 00:48:53,764
A LUCKY CRAB SHELL
PRIZE: DINING VOUCHER

1288
00:48:53,830 --> 00:48:57,134
-It was a huge piece of shell.
-I thought it was a tooth.

1289
00:48:57,200 --> 00:48:58,835
But it was crab shell.

1290
00:48:58,902 --> 00:49:00,470
-We're sorry.
-I knew something was up.

1291
00:49:00,537 --> 00:49:02,372
It's been deep-fried.

1292
00:49:02,439 --> 00:49:04,107
A BITE OF GAT FRITTER

1293
00:49:04,174 --> 00:49:05,175
Wow.

1294
00:49:05,642 --> 00:49:07,878
THE CRISPY SOUND HITS EVERYONE'S EARS

1295
00:49:07,945 --> 00:49:10,347
-It's so crispy.
-He delivered.

1296
00:49:10,414 --> 00:49:12,516
It wasn't just for decoration.

1297
00:49:12,582 --> 00:49:14,751
-And it's seasoned well.
-Right?

1298
00:49:14,818 --> 00:49:16,420
-Is it seasoned?
-Yes, perfectly.

1299
00:49:16,486 --> 00:49:19,756
He made the fritter
as a token of respect to you.

1300
00:49:19,823 --> 00:49:21,925
I love the shape too.

1301
00:49:21,992 --> 00:49:25,028
It looks cool on the dish
with this as the accent piece.

1302
00:49:25,095 --> 00:49:27,264
Will Americans also like it?

1303
00:49:27,831 --> 00:49:29,166
-Definitely.
-Really?

1304
00:49:29,232 --> 00:49:34,538
It has a creamy, soupy texture,

1305
00:49:34,604 --> 00:49:36,940
so it's hard to imagine
this is made with seaweed.

1306
00:49:37,975 --> 00:49:42,012
Team Ho-young and Sam
made three different dishes.

1307
00:49:42,079 --> 00:49:43,413
Miyeok Pop.

1308
00:49:43,480 --> 00:49:45,916
CRISPY SEAWEED MENBOSHA

1309
00:49:45,983 --> 00:49:50,287
AND REFRESHING SEAWEED UDON WITH LIME

1310
00:49:50,354 --> 00:49:53,156
SWEET AND SOUR SEAWEED SALAD,
BUBBLY LIKE SODA

1311
00:49:53,724 --> 00:49:57,394
JUNG HO-YOUNG & SAM KIM,
MIYEOK POP BY THE ATTENTION HUNTERS

1312
00:49:58,695 --> 00:50:01,365
Can we add a little more sauce?

1313
00:50:01,431 --> 00:50:02,666
Should I say it?

1314
00:50:02,733 --> 00:50:07,270
The noodles would've soaked up the soup,

1315
00:50:07,337 --> 00:50:08,839
so may we add a little more?

1316
00:50:08,905 --> 00:50:10,574
Come and pour a little more.

1317
00:50:11,341 --> 00:50:13,243
-Go on.
-Hurry up.

1318
00:50:13,310 --> 00:50:15,379
He orders him around again!

1319
00:50:15,445 --> 00:50:17,481
-He made Sam do that too.
-"Go on."

1320
00:50:17,547 --> 00:50:19,950
Do you want to stand here for a moment?

1321
00:50:20,751 --> 00:50:23,820
He makes Sam do all kinds of things.

1322
00:50:23,887 --> 00:50:25,422
And Sam listens.

1323
00:50:25,489 --> 00:50:29,292
She moved abroad when she was five.

1324
00:50:30,127 --> 00:50:32,429
What's the udon like?

1325
00:50:32,496 --> 00:50:33,663
Mmm.

1326
00:50:34,064 --> 00:50:35,832
CURIOUS

1327
00:50:35,899 --> 00:50:37,868
Sam pulled the noodles.

1328
00:50:39,936 --> 00:50:41,138
What are the noodles like?

1329
00:50:41,204 --> 00:50:42,973
They're very soft.

1330
00:50:44,074 --> 00:50:45,075
The dough was thick.

1331
00:50:45,142 --> 00:50:47,244
They're also chewy and thin.

1332
00:50:47,310 --> 00:50:50,147
-I like how thin the noodles are.
-Do you like it?

1333
00:50:51,681 --> 00:50:53,283
You made good noodles.

1334
00:50:53,350 --> 00:50:55,018
Ho-young compliments Sam.

1335
00:50:55,085 --> 00:50:56,453
-Great job.
-"Great job."

1336
00:50:59,689 --> 00:51:02,492
SHOOTING OUT A LOOK

1337
00:51:02,559 --> 00:51:05,495
She didn't look at Hyun-suk and Poong
when she had their food.

1338
00:51:05,562 --> 00:51:09,166
-But she looked at the chefs right now.
-She looked.

1339
00:51:10,467 --> 00:51:13,136
Dip it in the chili sauce.

1340
00:51:13,203 --> 00:51:14,638
Oh, my.

1341
00:51:14,704 --> 00:51:15,939
MILKY-WHITE FILLING INSIDE

1342
00:51:16,006 --> 00:51:16,840
Oh, my.

1343
00:51:16,907 --> 00:51:18,642
-Goodness.
-What's inside?

1344
00:51:18,708 --> 00:51:21,244
<i>-Shrimp and pork belly.</i>
<i>-Shrimp…</i>

1345
00:51:21,311 --> 00:51:23,814
-Pork belly. Did you grind it?
-Oh, pork belly!

1346
00:51:23,880 --> 00:51:27,084
-Then wrapped with <i>miyeok</i> and fried.
-Wrapped and deep-fried.

1347
00:51:27,150 --> 00:51:28,618
<i>Menbosha</i>.

1348
00:51:28,685 --> 00:51:30,654
Now, how is the taste?

1349
00:51:30,720 --> 00:51:31,688
WHAT'S THE MENBOSHA LIKE?

1350
00:51:31,755 --> 00:51:33,490
She seems to enjoy it a lot.

1351
00:51:34,324 --> 00:51:35,459
ANOTHER BITE

1352
00:51:35,525 --> 00:51:37,360
What's deep-fried <i>miyeok</i> like?

1353
00:51:37,761 --> 00:51:39,429
NERVOUS

1354
00:51:39,496 --> 00:51:42,232
Some parts are nicely deep-fried, but…

1355
00:51:42,566 --> 00:51:44,401
BUT?

1356
00:51:44,468 --> 00:51:46,570
The textures are a bit different.

1357
00:51:46,636 --> 00:51:48,939
-The mouthfeel?
-Yes, the mouthfeel is different.

1358
00:51:49,005 --> 00:51:51,708
<i>Miyeok</i> has different thicknesses.

1359
00:51:51,775 --> 00:51:53,743
I tried to make it as even as possible,

1360
00:51:53,810 --> 00:51:57,114
but the thicker portion
may seem a bit undercooked.

1361
00:51:57,180 --> 00:51:58,415
Who deep-fried these?

1362
00:51:58,482 --> 00:52:00,517
Goodness, Ho-young.

1363
00:52:00,584 --> 00:52:02,385
-You should've made it even.
-Right.

1364
00:52:02,452 --> 00:52:05,322
Sam was the one who wrapped it.

1365
00:52:05,622 --> 00:52:06,623
NOT OUR PROBLEM

1366
00:52:06,690 --> 00:52:10,093
-You should've made it even.
-He's blaming him.

1367
00:52:10,160 --> 00:52:12,996
-I had too much to do.
-"If it goes well, it's thanks to me."

1368
00:52:13,063 --> 00:52:15,732
He only did the cooking
while I did all the prepping.

1369
00:52:15,799 --> 00:52:17,367
Sam feels falsely accused.

1370
00:52:17,434 --> 00:52:19,536
Lastly, this one.

1371
00:52:19,603 --> 00:52:23,306
Try everything together.
Cucumber, <i>miyeok</i>, abalone, and shrimp.

1372
00:52:23,373 --> 00:52:24,708
I see some onion too.

1373
00:52:24,774 --> 00:52:26,376
-Yes, it's in there.
-Onion.

1374
00:52:27,077 --> 00:52:29,412
SHRIMP, CUCUMBER, ONION FIRST

1375
00:52:29,479 --> 00:52:30,313
Abalone.

1376
00:52:31,181 --> 00:52:33,617
A BITE OF ABALONE

1377
00:52:33,683 --> 00:52:35,919
She likes <i>miyeok</i>.

1378
00:52:35,986 --> 00:52:38,355
It goes really well
with sweet and sour soy sauce.

1379
00:52:38,421 --> 00:52:40,223
-Sweet and sour soy sauce.
-What's it like?

1380
00:52:40,290 --> 00:52:42,592
Compared to this sauce<i>…</i>

1381
00:52:42,659 --> 00:52:44,327
-Is it sour?
-<i>…</i>it's a bit more sour.

1382
00:52:44,394 --> 00:52:45,529
Hence, sweet and sour salad.

1383
00:52:46,096 --> 00:52:48,999
This was a little sweeter.

1384
00:52:49,065 --> 00:52:52,068
They probably had her eat the udon first
because this is more sour.

1385
00:52:52,135 --> 00:52:54,104
Please try it with the <i>menbosha</i>.

1386
00:52:54,171 --> 00:52:57,841
-With <i>menbosha</i>.
-Cut it up and try it with the <i>menbosha</i>.

1387
00:52:57,908 --> 00:53:00,177
Should she pick it up like a side dish?

1388
00:53:00,243 --> 00:53:01,845
That's what you mean.

1389
00:53:01,912 --> 00:53:05,115
Leejung, why don't you get a taste too?

1390
00:53:05,182 --> 00:53:07,217
She's here today as a plus one.

1391
00:53:07,284 --> 00:53:09,352
Today's meal looks nice.

1392
00:53:09,619 --> 00:53:11,788
THE TUBBY TWINS EAT
AS THE CHEFS' REPRESENTATIVE

1393
00:53:11,855 --> 00:53:14,157
Hyun-suk and Poong's BMB.

1394
00:53:14,224 --> 00:53:17,093
Try it with the sauce and the fritters.

1395
00:53:17,661 --> 00:53:18,628
Crab and seaweed.

1396
00:53:18,695 --> 00:53:20,397
-Mmm.
-BMB.

1397
00:53:20,463 --> 00:53:21,431
Mmm.

1398
00:53:22,766 --> 00:53:25,535
She looks at Chef Hyun-suk.

1399
00:53:25,602 --> 00:53:28,738
Her ideal type.

1400
00:53:28,805 --> 00:53:30,073
A DISH MADE BY HER IDEAL TYPE

1401
00:53:30,640 --> 00:53:33,376
-Is it good?
-It's so good.

1402
00:53:33,443 --> 00:53:35,212
-Let's dig in.
-Okay.

1403
00:53:35,278 --> 00:53:37,013
The twins.

1404
00:53:37,080 --> 00:53:39,316
-The sauce must be nice.
-It's really good.

1405
00:53:39,382 --> 00:53:41,685
At first, it was too salty,

1406
00:53:41,751 --> 00:53:43,720
so I helped them find the right taste.

1407
00:53:43,787 --> 00:53:45,822
What's it like, Nam-no?

1408
00:53:45,889 --> 00:53:47,958
-It reminds me of that thing.
-What?

1409
00:53:48,024 --> 00:53:51,294
-Clam chowder.
-Yes, you're right.

1410
00:53:51,361 --> 00:53:53,463
The seafood flavor hits me really hard.

1411
00:53:53,530 --> 00:53:55,265
It's thanks to the <i>miyeok</i>.

1412
00:53:55,332 --> 00:53:57,734
-<i>Miyeok</i> is the main ingredient here.
-The influence of the <i>miyeok</i>.

1413
00:53:57,801 --> 00:54:01,938
As she mentioned before,
you can feel many different textures.

1414
00:54:02,005 --> 00:54:04,341
<i>This is crispy, this is soft,</i>

1415
00:54:04,407 --> 00:54:05,842
<i>the sauce is creamy,</i>

1416
00:54:05,909 --> 00:54:08,011
and it's not overly greasy.

1417
00:54:08,078 --> 00:54:09,980
It's really good.

1418
00:54:10,046 --> 00:54:11,881
-Look at that.
-It was so good.

1419
00:54:11,948 --> 00:54:13,850
She ate everything.

1420
00:54:13,917 --> 00:54:16,353
Next, Miyeok Pop.

1421
00:54:16,953 --> 00:54:18,321
Mmm.

1422
00:54:18,388 --> 00:54:22,058
This reminds me of cold buckwheat noodles.

1423
00:54:22,125 --> 00:54:24,894
-Cold buckwheat noodles? I see.
-Yes.

1424
00:54:25,595 --> 00:54:26,763
It's so good.

1425
00:54:28,999 --> 00:54:31,167
NAM-NO THE NOODLE ENTHUSIAST
TAKES A BIG BITE

1426
00:54:31,234 --> 00:54:33,570
-He makes it look so good.
-Mmm.

1427
00:54:34,638 --> 00:54:36,539
How is it, Nam-no?

1428
00:54:36,606 --> 00:54:39,242
-It's…
-Look at the seaweed on his face.

1429
00:54:39,309 --> 00:54:40,410
Is that a mole or seaweed?

1430
00:54:40,477 --> 00:54:44,114
I throw in lots of roasted seaweed flakes
when I eat cold udon.

1431
00:54:44,180 --> 00:54:46,950
It feels like it's been replaced
with another kind of seaweed.

1432
00:54:47,017 --> 00:54:49,819
-You're right.
-The seaweed flavor is nice and subtle,

1433
00:54:49,886 --> 00:54:51,888
and it goes so well with lime.

1434
00:54:51,955 --> 00:54:54,057
It's a wonderful dish
for the middle of summer.

1435
00:54:54,124 --> 00:54:55,992
-Yes.
-It would be nice.

1436
00:54:56,059 --> 00:54:57,761
-Of course.
-It's cold and refreshing.

1437
00:54:57,827 --> 00:54:59,896
-Time to choose.
-It's now time to choose.

1438
00:54:59,963 --> 00:55:02,932
You'll have to make a choice,
Director Kang.

1439
00:55:02,999 --> 00:55:05,869
<i>Press one to choose Ho-young and Sam,</i>

1440
00:55:05,935 --> 00:55:08,705
<i>and two to choose Hyun-suk and Poong.</i>

1441
00:55:08,772 --> 00:55:11,174
Let's find out the result
of the team round!

1442
00:55:11,241 --> 00:55:12,275
Show us!

1443
00:55:13,209 --> 00:55:15,111
K-Food <i>Miyeok </i>Hunters.

1444
00:55:15,178 --> 00:55:17,681
Will it go to Team Hyun-suk and Poong?

1445
00:55:17,747 --> 00:55:20,884
Or will it be Team Ho-young and Sam?

1446
00:55:20,950 --> 00:55:22,352
Who did Director Kang choose?

1447
00:55:22,419 --> 00:55:24,721
Which team did she pick?

1448
00:55:24,788 --> 00:55:27,223
Show us the winner!

1449
00:55:27,290 --> 00:55:28,858
Which team won?

1450
00:55:28,925 --> 00:55:30,126
CHOI HYUN-SUK AND KIM POONG WIN

1451
00:55:30,193 --> 00:55:31,294
It's Hyun-suk and Poong.

1452
00:55:31,828 --> 00:55:33,630
CHOI HYUN-SUK AND KIM POONG'S BMB WINS

1453
00:55:33,697 --> 00:55:35,999
It's Hyun-suk and Poong.

1454
00:55:36,066 --> 00:55:38,001
FLAP, FLAP

1455
00:55:38,068 --> 00:55:40,804
Look how excited they are.

1456
00:55:41,771 --> 00:55:45,041
A FLASHY CELEBRATION
AFTER THEIR SUCCESSFUL STAR HUNT

1457
00:55:45,108 --> 00:55:48,078
They worked as a team
for the first time today,

1458
00:55:48,144 --> 00:55:49,646
and they end with a big hug.

1459
00:55:49,713 --> 00:55:52,248
-They were never on such good terms.
-Not at all.

1460
00:55:52,315 --> 00:55:53,783
That's how scary stars can be.

1461
00:55:53,850 --> 00:55:55,418
It was a tough choice.

1462
00:55:55,485 --> 00:55:57,320
Everything I had was so delicious.

1463
00:55:57,387 --> 00:55:58,588
However,

1464
00:55:58,655 --> 00:56:02,926
I've never had anything
like that creamy <i>miyeok</i> soup.

1465
00:56:02,992 --> 00:56:06,129
-The seaweed sauce.
-It was so new. The sauce, yes.

1466
00:56:06,196 --> 00:56:07,731
But everything was good!

1467
00:56:07,797 --> 00:56:10,233
-It was.
-I enjoyed it a lot.

1468
00:56:10,300 --> 00:56:14,104
Please get the stars
from Director Maggie Kang!

1469
00:56:14,170 --> 00:56:15,872
-Two in total.
-They receive a star each

1470
00:56:15,939 --> 00:56:17,507
from Director Maggie Kang!

1471
00:56:17,574 --> 00:56:19,342
Congratulations!

1472
00:56:19,409 --> 00:56:21,077
CONGRATULATIONS

1473
00:56:21,144 --> 00:56:23,546
-It was delicious.
-They take the stars.

1474
00:56:23,613 --> 00:56:28,385
<i>This is the second round with ingredients</i>
<i>from Director Kang's fridge.</i>

1475
00:56:28,451 --> 00:56:32,088
This is the first three-on-one
tag-team round of the show.

1476
00:56:32,155 --> 00:56:34,391
The Jinu of the show, Son Jong-won,

1477
00:56:34,457 --> 00:56:37,160
-is up against the Huntrix of the show.
-They're Huntrix?

1478
00:56:37,227 --> 00:56:39,362
You're right. Hey.

1479
00:56:39,429 --> 00:56:40,930
I don't think they're Huntrix.

1480
00:56:40,997 --> 00:56:42,599
More like Hurtrix.

1481
00:56:42,665 --> 00:56:43,933
-I'm hurt.
-Hurt.

1482
00:56:44,000 --> 00:56:45,835
-Hurtrix?
-Aren't they Hurtrix?

1483
00:56:45,902 --> 00:56:48,905
Chef Jong-won has five stars,

1484
00:56:48,972 --> 00:56:51,875
and the three of them
have six stars in total.

1485
00:56:51,941 --> 00:56:53,943
You're on par with him.

1486
00:56:54,010 --> 00:56:56,379
Eun-yeong has four stars.

1487
00:56:56,446 --> 00:56:58,381
-Have we taken a break?
-The twins have one each.

1488
00:56:58,448 --> 00:57:00,250
What's going on with your performances?

1489
00:57:00,316 --> 00:57:02,018
Please win this one for us.

1490
00:57:02,852 --> 00:57:04,254
Isn't it suffocating, Eun-yeong?

1491
00:57:04,320 --> 00:57:06,156
-Actually, I…
-She's stuck in the middle.

1492
00:57:06,222 --> 00:57:07,557
-Right here…
-You look trapped.

1493
00:57:07,624 --> 00:57:09,826
I can hear her, but can't see her.

1494
00:57:10,093 --> 00:57:11,694
COMPLETE OBSTRUCTION

1495
00:57:11,761 --> 00:57:12,595
It looks suffocating.

1496
00:57:12,662 --> 00:57:15,999
I heard Chef Sung-jun
is determined to win this round.

1497
00:57:16,065 --> 00:57:18,201
Even if the three of us team up,

1498
00:57:18,268 --> 00:57:20,670
we'll never be as buzzworthy
as Chef Jong-won.

1499
00:57:21,104 --> 00:57:22,739
A LEVEL-HEADED METACOGNITIVE MAN

1500
00:57:22,806 --> 00:57:25,041
So we'll take him down today,
no matter what.

1501
00:57:25,108 --> 00:57:26,643
I came determined.

1502
00:57:26,709 --> 00:57:29,045
We all have
about the same number of stars, too.

1503
00:57:29,112 --> 00:57:33,016
What do you think
about that team of three, Jong-won?

1504
00:57:33,082 --> 00:57:36,319
I believe cooking is something
many people do together.

1505
00:57:36,386 --> 00:57:38,121
I'm looking forward to finding out

1506
00:57:38,188 --> 00:57:40,223
-how good their dish will be.
-Is that so?

1507
00:57:40,290 --> 00:57:42,992
That's not what you said
in the green room.

1508
00:57:43,059 --> 00:57:44,594
-Do we have a transcript?
-We do.

1509
00:57:44,661 --> 00:57:46,729
-I knew it.
-In the green room, he said,

1510
00:57:46,796 --> 00:57:50,166
"Those three are a motley crew."

1511
00:57:50,233 --> 00:57:52,936
"I would rather cook alone
than cook with them."

1512
00:57:53,002 --> 00:57:54,938
-What did you mean by this?
-It's true.

1513
00:57:55,004 --> 00:57:57,607
They were saying that
about themselves in the green room.

1514
00:57:57,674 --> 00:58:01,377
To me, Chef Nam-no seems
easily distracted,

1515
00:58:01,444 --> 00:58:03,213
so I doubt he'll be helpful.

1516
00:58:03,279 --> 00:58:04,414
Chef Sung-jun

1517
00:58:04,481 --> 00:58:06,749
wants to be highly buzzworthy,

1518
00:58:06,816 --> 00:58:08,718
so in order to become a bigger issue,

1519
00:58:08,785 --> 00:58:11,821
he probably couldn't care less
about his team's victory.

1520
00:58:11,888 --> 00:58:12,755
You're correct.

1521
00:58:12,822 --> 00:58:14,591
I'm a bit worried about Chef Eun-yeong.

1522
00:58:14,657 --> 00:58:17,494
-I should start some trouble today.
-That's true.

1523
00:58:17,560 --> 00:58:20,196
Who's the leader among you three?

1524
00:58:20,263 --> 00:58:21,364
-Me.
-It's me.

1525
00:58:21,431 --> 00:58:23,900
-What? Hey.
-What are you doing? Drop your hand.

1526
00:58:23,967 --> 00:58:25,535
LOVES THIS SKIT

1527
00:58:25,602 --> 00:58:27,570
-Of course, it's me.
-It's me.

1528
00:58:27,637 --> 00:58:29,572
The more they act like this,

1529
00:58:29,639 --> 00:58:31,341
-the bigger the burden is on him.
-Why?

1530
00:58:31,407 --> 00:58:34,511
-It's great.
-He's thinking, "I can't lose to them."

1531
00:58:34,944 --> 00:58:35,879
BUNCH OF HYENAS

1532
00:58:35,945 --> 00:58:37,981
-What if he loses?
-Well, if he loses…

1533
00:58:38,047 --> 00:58:40,149
-Let's win this one.
-We have to.

1534
00:58:40,216 --> 00:58:41,985
We've played as a team. Let's do this.

1535
00:58:42,819 --> 00:58:44,821
CHEF JONG-WON'S INGREDIENTS:
GLUTINOUS RICE POWDER, MAKGEOLLI

1536
00:58:44,888 --> 00:58:46,990
GRAIN SYRUP, GINGER CHEONG,
CINNAMON POWDER, BEEF JERKY, AND MORE

1537
00:58:47,056 --> 00:58:49,926
What are you making, Chef Jong-won?

1538
00:58:49,993 --> 00:58:52,295
The name of my dish is as follows.

1539
00:58:52,362 --> 00:58:55,498
Is This Hangwa

1540
00:58:55,565 --> 00:58:58,334
Worthy of <i>KDH 2?</i>

1541
00:58:58,401 --> 00:58:59,769
That's way too long.

1542
00:58:59,836 --> 00:59:01,604
-He's making <i>hangwa</i>.
-Korean confection.

1543
00:59:01,671 --> 00:59:04,274
-He must be making <i>hangwa</i>.
-He's trying to win her heart.

1544
00:59:04,340 --> 00:59:07,143
-He even did this pose.
-He's changed.

1545
00:59:08,044 --> 00:59:10,413
-Should we do it too?
-Yes, let's do it.

1546
00:59:10,480 --> 00:59:11,748
Are you making <i>hangwa</i>?

1547
00:59:11,814 --> 00:59:14,617
I'll be making three types of <i>hangwa</i>.

1548
00:59:14,684 --> 00:59:17,020
First, I'll make <i>juak</i>, Gaeseong <i>juak</i>.

1549
00:59:17,086 --> 00:59:18,955
-Gaeseong <i>juak</i>?
-I'll make that.

1550
00:59:19,022 --> 00:59:21,925
-It's pretty much a Korean donut.
-You're right.

1551
00:59:21,991 --> 00:59:25,228
I'll also make <i>gangjeong</i>, brittle.

1552
00:59:25,295 --> 00:59:28,364
-And beef jerky <i>dasik</i>, pressed cookie.
-<i>Dasik</i>?

1553
00:59:28,431 --> 00:59:30,366
You also said you liked <i>sikhye</i>,

1554
00:59:30,433 --> 00:59:33,836
so I prepared another way
of enjoying <i>sikhye </i>as a refreshment.

1555
00:59:33,903 --> 00:59:35,505
I'll make the most Korean desserts

1556
00:59:35,572 --> 00:59:37,040
-without adding any twists.
-Right.

1557
00:59:37,106 --> 00:59:39,576
I imagined the characters of <i>KDH 2</i>

1558
00:59:39,642 --> 00:59:44,380
<i>sitting in a </i>hanok<i> café</i>
<i>and enjoying everything together.</i>

1559
00:59:44,447 --> 00:59:48,017
-He even imagined a specific scene.
-Yes, he did.

1560
00:59:48,851 --> 00:59:50,587
SUNG-JUN & EUN-YEONG & NAM-NO'S
INGREDIENTS: PORK TENDERLOIN

1561
00:59:50,653 --> 00:59:53,022
BEEF SIRLOIN, WHOLE CHICKEN LEG, ZUCCHINI,
SHIITAKE, GOBINAMUL, CHWINAMUL, AND MORE

1562
00:59:53,089 --> 00:59:55,258
The young guns are up against him.

1563
00:59:55,325 --> 00:59:56,392
What are you making?

1564
00:59:56,459 --> 00:59:58,995
I Hope to See Myself in <i>KDH 2</i>

1565
00:59:59,062 --> 01:00:01,464
-is a dish made with noodles.
-Noodles.

1566
01:00:01,531 --> 01:00:05,401
Director Kang said she had fond memories
of eating Pyongyang <i>naengmyeon</i>,

1567
01:00:05,468 --> 01:00:07,604
so we decided to make
a traditional <i>jeongol</i> from Pyongyang,

1568
01:00:07,670 --> 01:00:09,739
-a dish called <i>eobok-jaengban.</i>
-<i>Eobok-jaengban</i>?

1569
01:00:09,806 --> 01:00:13,810
It's actually a dish
made to treat important guests.

1570
01:00:13,876 --> 01:00:15,345
It requires <i>namul</i>.

1571
01:00:15,411 --> 01:00:17,113
-Yes, it does.
-And lots of meat.

1572
01:00:17,180 --> 01:00:18,715
-And meat.
-Yes.

1573
01:00:18,781 --> 01:00:22,418
Many Koreans out there
don't know what <i>eobok-jaengban</i> is.

1574
01:00:22,485 --> 01:00:25,054
So I want to use this opportunity

1575
01:00:25,121 --> 01:00:28,691
to let many people find out
what <i>eobok-jaengban</i> is.

1576
01:00:28,758 --> 01:00:29,993
IF IT'S IN KDH 2, THE WORLD WILL KNOW

1577
01:00:30,059 --> 01:00:31,794
Which one of you should appear in <i>KDH 2?</i>

1578
01:00:31,861 --> 01:00:33,997
-Me, of course.
-It should be me.

1579
01:00:34,063 --> 01:00:34,897
DROP YOUR HAND

1580
01:00:34,964 --> 01:00:36,032
STIFF-ARM

1581
01:00:36,099 --> 01:00:37,000
Only me.

1582
01:00:37,066 --> 01:00:38,768
WILL IT BE OKAY?

1583
01:00:38,835 --> 01:00:40,503
Who's going to go first?

1584
01:00:40,570 --> 01:00:42,405
-Of course, it's me.
-And the last one?

1585
01:00:42,472 --> 01:00:45,208
-Him.
-Really?

1586
01:00:45,274 --> 01:00:47,844
-I should've gone first.
-At least they have an order.

1587
01:00:47,910 --> 01:00:52,015
All right, then.
Let us begin the cook-off.

1588
01:00:52,081 --> 01:00:53,082
I'm looking forward to it!

1589
01:00:53,149 --> 01:00:55,485
K-Food Inspo for <i>KDH 2.</i>

1590
01:00:55,551 --> 01:00:58,554
Which dish will she choose?

1591
01:00:58,621 --> 01:01:01,424
The K-chef we want to show off
to the whole world!

1592
01:01:01,491 --> 01:01:02,525
BLUSH

1593
01:01:02,592 --> 01:01:04,661
Jinu of the show, Chef Son Jong-won.

1594
01:01:04,727 --> 01:01:07,730
The idea of showing them to the world

1595
01:01:08,464 --> 01:01:09,899
is a bit…

1596
01:01:09,966 --> 01:01:11,601
Gosh. Yes.

1597
01:01:11,668 --> 01:01:14,037
It's a bit early
to present the young guns to the world.

1598
01:01:14,103 --> 01:01:16,706
-The Hurtrix of the show<i>…</i>
-"To the world."

1599
01:01:16,773 --> 01:01:17,874
<i>…</i>the three chefs.

1600
01:01:17,940 --> 01:01:20,610
This is the first
tag-team match of <i>Chef & My Fridge.</i>

1601
01:01:20,677 --> 01:01:21,711
-Wow.
-And now,

1602
01:01:21,778 --> 01:01:24,480
-who'll be a bigger inspiration for <i>KDH 2?</i>
-It's an emergency.

1603
01:01:24,547 --> 01:01:28,418
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1604
01:01:28,918 --> 01:01:30,620
Begin!

1605
01:01:31,654 --> 01:01:32,555
Move aside!

1606
01:01:32,622 --> 01:01:35,091
-Go away.
-Hurry up.

1607
01:01:35,158 --> 01:01:36,559
They both left.

1608
01:01:36,626 --> 01:01:39,562
You must fight one-on-one
when you're in the kitchen.

1609
01:01:39,629 --> 01:01:41,531
He's going in right away.

1610
01:01:41,597 --> 01:01:45,001
-It's probably the <i>juak </i>syrup.
-Is he boiling those?

1611
01:01:45,802 --> 01:01:47,236
-Glutinous rice powder?
-It is.

1612
01:01:47,303 --> 01:01:48,404
Glutinous rice powder?

1613
01:01:48,471 --> 01:01:51,140
<i>Juak</i> dough is usually made with hot water.

1614
01:01:51,207 --> 01:01:53,076
It's often kneaded with hot water.

1615
01:01:53,142 --> 01:01:56,612
And there are touches
of <i>makgeolli</i> or other liquor

1616
01:01:56,679 --> 01:01:58,781
-in the dough too.
-I see.

1617
01:01:58,848 --> 01:02:00,049
A-HA

1618
01:02:00,616 --> 01:02:01,718
It's my turn.

1619
01:02:01,784 --> 01:02:03,653
-What's that meat?
-Pork.

1620
01:02:03,920 --> 01:02:05,288
BEEF SIRLOIN

1621
01:02:05,588 --> 01:02:09,726
SUNG-JUN'S TO-DO LIST:
BOIL MEAT, MAKE NOODLES, MAKE YUKJANG

1622
01:02:09,792 --> 01:02:10,626
No more.

1623
01:02:10,693 --> 01:02:12,095
Turn up the heat.

1624
01:02:12,161 --> 01:02:13,362
The heat.

1625
01:02:14,630 --> 01:02:16,365
I HAVE MY EYES ON YOU!

1626
01:02:16,432 --> 01:02:17,600
Cover it with a lid.

1627
01:02:17,667 --> 01:02:18,701
The veggies.

1628
01:02:18,768 --> 01:02:20,803
-Break them in half.
-Add some veggies.

1629
01:02:21,037 --> 01:02:22,472
MOVING SLOWLY

1630
01:02:23,706 --> 01:02:24,607
Add radish.

1631
01:02:24,674 --> 01:02:25,942
Did you eat fried chicken last night?
You're slow.

1632
01:02:26,008 --> 01:02:27,777
-Add radish.
-Why am I so sluggish?

1633
01:02:27,844 --> 01:02:30,346
-Why won't you add radish?
-They must cook that for a while.

1634
01:02:30,413 --> 01:02:32,081
Drain some water then.

1635
01:02:32,148 --> 01:02:33,783
It won't work well with that much water.

1636
01:02:33,850 --> 01:02:36,452
That's enough water
to shoot out when it steams.

1637
01:02:36,519 --> 01:02:38,054
-Really?
-Throw out some water!

1638
01:02:38,121 --> 01:02:40,156
It's okay. It'll work.

1639
01:02:40,223 --> 01:02:42,658
-Poong just gave advice, but…
-That's too much water.

1640
01:02:42,725 --> 01:02:43,626
It'll explode.

1641
01:02:43,693 --> 01:02:45,294
THE YOUNG GUNS IGNORED POONG

1642
01:02:45,361 --> 01:02:46,529
THE JINU OF THE SHOW IS UP!

1643
01:02:48,131 --> 01:02:50,266
BEGINS TO KNEAD JUAK DOUGH!

1644
01:02:51,968 --> 01:02:53,803
CUTTING INTO SMALLER PIECES

1645
01:02:53,870 --> 01:02:55,738
AND IT GOES WHERE?

1646
01:02:55,805 --> 01:02:58,274
He's shaping the <i>juak</i> now.

1647
01:02:58,341 --> 01:03:00,710
-He's using a precision scale.
-He's measuring them?

1648
01:03:00,777 --> 01:03:01,811
WOW

1649
01:03:01,878 --> 01:03:02,879
That's a thing?

1650
01:03:02,945 --> 01:03:05,281
It's a precision scale
that can measure down to 0.1 g.

1651
01:03:05,348 --> 01:03:07,917
-It can measure down to 0.1 g?
-That's awesome.

1652
01:03:07,984 --> 01:03:11,020
He weighs them first. So precise.

1653
01:03:11,087 --> 01:03:12,855
Looking cool, Jong-won.

1654
01:03:12,922 --> 01:03:15,858
It's been 2 minutes and 20 seconds.

1655
01:03:15,925 --> 01:03:17,827
Jong-won shapes the <i>juak</i>.

1656
01:03:17,894 --> 01:03:19,929
-They look nice.
-Yes.

1657
01:03:20,429 --> 01:03:24,333
He'll cook that in oil now,

1658
01:03:24,400 --> 01:03:26,602
but the temperature cannot be high.

1659
01:03:26,669 --> 01:03:29,305
It needs to cook in a low temperature,
so it takes a while.

1660
01:03:30,473 --> 01:03:31,407
STARCH

1661
01:03:31,474 --> 01:03:33,976
NEXT MISSION: MAKE NOODLES!

1662
01:03:34,043 --> 01:03:34,877
STARCH

1663
01:03:35,611 --> 01:03:36,679
It's too wet.

1664
01:03:36,746 --> 01:03:38,815
Hey, why are you doing this?

1665
01:03:38,881 --> 01:03:40,049
He added too much water.

1666
01:03:40,116 --> 01:03:42,251
That's like batter for green onion <i>jeon</i>.

1667
01:03:42,318 --> 01:03:44,987
-What?
-He made <i>jeon</i> batter, instead of dough.

1668
01:03:45,054 --> 01:03:48,157
Why are you telling on him?
He's on your team!

1669
01:03:48,224 --> 01:03:50,193
Why are you telling on him?

1670
01:03:50,259 --> 01:03:52,562
Oh, right. He's on our team.

1671
01:03:52,628 --> 01:03:54,997
He's doing well. Good job with the dough.

1672
01:03:55,064 --> 01:03:57,600
-He's not making frying batter.
-It's a dough to make noodles.

1673
01:03:57,667 --> 01:03:59,402
It should be drier.

1674
01:03:59,468 --> 01:04:01,404
It should be dry,

1675
01:04:01,470 --> 01:04:04,006
but it must be runny.

1676
01:04:04,073 --> 01:04:05,608
Good. Nice dough.

1677
01:04:05,675 --> 01:04:06,676
It's me.

1678
01:04:06,742 --> 01:04:08,678
You're already
2 minutes and 30 seconds in.

1679
01:04:08,744 --> 01:04:10,146
-What? Already?
-Hurry up.

1680
01:04:10,213 --> 01:04:12,748
-Will you move faster?
-This is the most important step.

1681
01:04:12,815 --> 01:04:15,785
"The most important…"
Just please move faster.

1682
01:04:15,852 --> 01:04:16,919
I got this.

1683
01:04:16,986 --> 01:04:18,721
-You only get five minutes.
-We're ruined.

1684
01:04:18,788 --> 01:04:20,056
-You're ruined?
-Ruined?

1685
01:04:20,122 --> 01:04:22,792
-It's ruined?
-We're ruined. There's no time.

1686
01:04:22,859 --> 01:04:26,162
I don't know what he'll do with the dough,
but it looks too dry to make noodles.

1687
01:04:26,229 --> 01:04:28,464
-What are you doing?
-Why aren't you making <i>yukjang?</i>

1688
01:04:28,531 --> 01:04:29,832
<i>Yukjang</i>.

1689
01:04:29,899 --> 01:04:31,734
WHILE THE DOUGH SITS, MAKE YUKJANG

1690
01:04:32,168 --> 01:04:33,803
-<i>Yukjang</i>.
-<i>Yukjang</i>.

1691
01:04:33,870 --> 01:04:36,772
Bring the pot and throw them in at once.
Why are you going back and forth?

1692
01:04:36,839 --> 01:04:38,841
Don't be nervous.

1693
01:04:38,908 --> 01:04:42,478
Now, water. A cup of soy sauce?
How about half?

1694
01:04:42,545 --> 01:04:44,580
-No, more.
-This team is thinking,

1695
01:04:44,647 --> 01:04:47,783
"The next person will figure it out."

1696
01:04:47,850 --> 01:04:51,420
That means Nam-no will
have to wrap it up nicely.

1697
01:04:51,954 --> 01:04:53,990
Nam-no will have to face the consequences.

1698
01:04:54,056 --> 01:04:55,625
-Isn't that too sweet?
-Add sugar!

1699
01:04:55,691 --> 01:04:56,792
-Sugar.
-Sugar?

1700
01:04:56,859 --> 01:04:58,628
-Starch syrup!
-Starch syrup too?

1701
01:04:58,694 --> 01:04:59,996
-It's too sweet!
-Isn't it too sweet?

1702
01:05:00,062 --> 01:05:01,364
-No.
-That's enough.

1703
01:05:01,430 --> 01:05:02,865
No, <i>yukjang </i>has to be sweet!

1704
01:05:02,932 --> 01:05:04,233
It has to be sweet?

1705
01:05:04,300 --> 01:05:06,402
-It's way too sweet.
-Just stay quiet.

1706
01:05:06,469 --> 01:05:08,070
Is this Japanese cuisine?

1707
01:05:08,137 --> 01:05:10,139
There are too many captains on the boat.

1708
01:05:10,206 --> 01:05:11,073
ANYHOW, HE MADE YUKJANG TOO

1709
01:05:11,140 --> 01:05:12,375
-Starch syrup!
-Starch syrup too?

1710
01:05:12,441 --> 01:05:13,643
They're so loud.

1711
01:05:14,510 --> 01:05:18,180
4. BOIL SIKHYE WITH YUJA CHEONG

1712
01:05:18,414 --> 01:05:19,548
BEEF JERKY

1713
01:05:21,050 --> 01:05:23,052
GRINDING BEEF JERKY FINELY IN A BLENDER

1714
01:05:23,119 --> 01:05:25,087
-He's grinding beef jerky.
-Grinding beef jerky.

1715
01:05:25,388 --> 01:05:26,355
GULP

1716
01:05:27,123 --> 01:05:29,625
He'll probably make <i>dasik </i>with that.

1717
01:05:29,825 --> 01:05:30,826
OHHH

1718
01:05:31,227 --> 01:05:33,796
Can you make <i>dasik </i>with beef jerky?
Is that a thing?

1719
01:05:33,863 --> 01:05:34,697
STARCH SYRUP

1720
01:05:34,764 --> 01:05:38,034
5. BOIL STARCH SYRUP AND SUGAR

1721
01:05:38,100 --> 01:05:40,369
He has to drop the <i>gangjeong</i>

1722
01:05:40,436 --> 01:05:43,072
into that sugary water later.

1723
01:05:43,139 --> 01:05:47,243
-He must coat them before cooking them.
-Yes, that's the <i>hangwa</i> he's making.

1724
01:05:47,310 --> 01:05:49,111
-I must make the noodles.
-A minute and a half.

1725
01:05:49,178 --> 01:05:50,746
-The noodles.
-I need to make them.

1726
01:05:50,813 --> 01:05:52,815
You have to make the noodles!

1727
01:05:52,882 --> 01:05:54,216
You have to make it.

1728
01:05:54,283 --> 01:05:55,918
-That's something you need to do.
-The time.

1729
01:05:57,186 --> 01:05:59,121
-Just a little.
-Please.

1730
01:05:59,722 --> 01:06:01,457
Give me just one minute.

1731
01:06:01,524 --> 01:06:04,260
If the dough is too dry,
it'll rip as it goes through.

1732
01:06:04,327 --> 01:06:05,861
Goodness.

1733
01:06:05,928 --> 01:06:07,096
It's breaking.

1734
01:06:07,163 --> 01:06:09,332
You can always layer it.

1735
01:06:09,398 --> 01:06:10,900
Yes, layer it.

1736
01:06:10,967 --> 01:06:12,201
Great job, Sung-jun!

1737
01:06:12,268 --> 01:06:13,936
Great job!

1738
01:06:14,003 --> 01:06:15,304
-It's me.
-It's too dry.

1739
01:06:15,371 --> 01:06:17,340
You have 11 minutes left.

1740
01:06:17,406 --> 01:06:19,675
It's not going to work.

1741
01:06:19,742 --> 01:06:21,944
You have to get ready.

1742
01:06:22,011 --> 01:06:23,446
Just make <i>sujebi</i>, hand-pulled dough.

1743
01:06:23,512 --> 01:06:26,115
-Yes, make <i>sujebi</i>. That's Korean too.
-No.

1744
01:06:26,182 --> 01:06:27,650
Make <i>sujebi</i>.

1745
01:06:27,717 --> 01:06:29,085
You have to make the noodles.

1746
01:06:29,151 --> 01:06:30,653
The next person waits.

1747
01:06:30,987 --> 01:06:33,489
SUNG-JUN, I CAN STILL SEE YOUR HANDS

1748
01:06:33,556 --> 01:06:34,824
You can't help him.

1749
01:06:34,890 --> 01:06:37,059
-That's fine.
-Yes, that looks good.

1750
01:06:37,126 --> 01:06:38,594
Eun-yeong is already waiting?

1751
01:06:38,661 --> 01:06:39,795
We need noodles.

1752
01:06:39,862 --> 01:06:41,297
Chef Eun-yeong, wash your hands.

1753
01:06:41,364 --> 01:06:44,000
I think she's ready to take over.
She's washing her hands first.

1754
01:06:44,066 --> 01:06:47,436
-I can do it.
-Director Kang watches the cook-off…

1755
01:06:47,503 --> 01:06:49,605
-One more fold.
-…with a worried face.

1756
01:06:49,672 --> 01:06:50,606
One last time.

1757
01:06:50,673 --> 01:06:53,943
-What are you trying to do?
-Just make the noodles.

1758
01:06:54,010 --> 01:06:57,013
-Make the noodles. You have to do that.
-I'll do that.

1759
01:06:57,079 --> 01:06:59,081
What do you mean, "It's me"?

1760
01:06:59,148 --> 01:07:00,249
Like, "Hey, I got it"?

1761
01:07:00,316 --> 01:07:02,451
-You have ten minutes left.
-One more time.

1762
01:07:02,518 --> 01:07:04,220
-Good grief.
-What?

1763
01:07:04,286 --> 01:07:05,721
The noodles look good.

1764
01:07:05,788 --> 01:07:06,889
UNFOLDING

1765
01:07:06,956 --> 01:07:08,224
Whoa.

1766
01:07:08,290 --> 01:07:09,558
-Yes, that's it.
-Wow.

1767
01:07:09,625 --> 01:07:12,461
-It looks good.
-Wow.

1768
01:07:12,528 --> 01:07:13,696
That's nice.

1769
01:07:13,763 --> 01:07:14,830
This is who I am.

1770
01:07:15,464 --> 01:07:16,399
BUT THERE ARE NO STRANDS YET

1771
01:07:16,465 --> 01:07:19,201
Eun-yeong waits for him to tag her.

1772
01:07:19,635 --> 01:07:20,770
KWON SUNG-JUN…

1773
01:07:20,836 --> 01:07:22,538
HURRY IT UP ALREADY…

1774
01:07:23,105 --> 01:07:24,874
Nice!

1775
01:07:24,940 --> 01:07:25,875
He made the noodles.

1776
01:07:25,941 --> 01:07:29,278
-He's making the noodles.
-He made them!

1777
01:07:29,345 --> 01:07:31,414
-They look good.
-They do.

1778
01:07:31,480 --> 01:07:33,916
-Not bad.
-That's Sung-jun.

1779
01:07:33,983 --> 01:07:35,551
These look really good.

1780
01:07:36,318 --> 01:07:37,887
The go-to guy for pasta.

1781
01:07:38,654 --> 01:07:39,855
TAG, PARK EUN-YEONG

1782
01:07:39,922 --> 01:07:42,191
-I have to cook this.
-Tagged. It's Eun-yeong's turn.

1783
01:07:42,258 --> 01:07:44,493
-The meat.
-Sprinkle flour to prevent sticking.

1784
01:07:44,560 --> 01:07:46,495
-The flour.
-They're so noisy.

1785
01:07:47,129 --> 01:07:49,331
Hurry up. We're running behind.

1786
01:07:49,398 --> 01:07:51,233
-Hey.
-You're the reason why.

1787
01:07:51,300 --> 01:07:52,868
We're running behind. Hurry.

1788
01:07:52,935 --> 01:07:54,003
NO.1 AT BEING SHAMELESS!

1789
01:07:54,070 --> 01:07:56,238
You left a huge mess behind.

1790
01:07:56,305 --> 01:07:57,373
You have to add salt.

1791
01:07:57,440 --> 01:07:58,874
-It's right here.
-Salt?

1792
01:07:58,941 --> 01:08:01,444
-I wouldn't have done it if it were me.
-Add it to the water.

1793
01:08:01,510 --> 01:08:03,679
We have nine minutes left.

1794
01:08:03,746 --> 01:08:06,248
Jong-won must be distracted
with what's going on next to him.

1795
01:08:06,315 --> 01:08:09,752
Temperature control is everything
when you're making <i>juak</i>.

1796
01:08:09,819 --> 01:08:10,786
Right?

1797
01:08:10,853 --> 01:08:13,622
-You need to look for air bubbles.
-Hurry up. We're running behind!

1798
01:08:13,689 --> 01:08:16,659
-We're running behind.
-It has to look nice and milky-white.

1799
01:08:16,725 --> 01:08:19,895
-He ground some beef jerky.
-Whoa.

1800
01:08:19,962 --> 01:08:21,831
-It's nicely powdered.
-It's like red pepper powder.

1801
01:08:21,897 --> 01:08:23,799
-You can grind it like that?
-Like red pepper powder.

1802
01:08:24,667 --> 01:08:26,168
STARCH SYRUP

1803
01:08:26,235 --> 01:08:28,504
SUNFLOWER SEEDS

1804
01:08:28,571 --> 01:08:29,438
Sunflower seeds?

1805
01:08:29,505 --> 01:08:31,674
-I'm making <i>gangjeong</i>.
-<i>Gangjeong</i>.

1806
01:08:31,740 --> 01:08:33,342
He's making <i>gangjeong</i>.

1807
01:08:33,409 --> 01:08:34,777
He needs to cool it down.

1808
01:08:34,844 --> 01:08:37,113
He must cool it before cutting it.

1809
01:08:37,179 --> 01:08:40,182
He's using sunflower seeds,
sesame seeds, and pumpkin seeds.

1810
01:08:40,649 --> 01:08:41,550
STARCH SYRUP

1811
01:08:41,851 --> 01:08:42,685
PERILLA SEEDS

1812
01:08:42,751 --> 01:08:45,721
-What are those?
-Perilla seeds.

1813
01:08:45,788 --> 01:08:47,189
-Perilla seeds.
-Perilla seeds.

1814
01:08:47,256 --> 01:08:49,024
-Peeled perilla seeds.
-<i>Perilla gangjeong</i>.

1815
01:08:49,091 --> 01:08:50,493
6. MIX SEEDS WITH SYRUP AND COOL

1816
01:08:50,559 --> 01:08:52,261
Next, pumpkin seeds?

1817
01:08:52,328 --> 01:08:53,696
PUMPKIN SEEDS

1818
01:08:53,762 --> 01:08:55,264
Eun-yeong chops a zucchini.

1819
01:08:55,331 --> 01:08:56,665
ZUCCHINI

1820
01:08:56,732 --> 01:08:58,667
-Hurry up.
-You can do this.

1821
01:08:58,734 --> 01:08:59,702
You're too slow!

1822
01:09:00,703 --> 01:09:02,338
FASCINATING TO WATCH

1823
01:09:02,404 --> 01:09:03,772
Be quiet, you.

1824
01:09:03,839 --> 01:09:05,441
Keep your eyes on the noodles.

1825
01:09:05,508 --> 01:09:06,408
COOKED GOBINAMUL

1826
01:09:06,475 --> 01:09:07,943
You have to get them.

1827
01:09:08,010 --> 01:09:09,178
-Get them out.
-Get them.

1828
01:09:09,245 --> 01:09:10,746
And rinse them in cold water.

1829
01:09:10,813 --> 01:09:12,381
-Are you sure they're cooked?
-Hurry.

1830
01:09:12,448 --> 01:09:14,383
-We'll cook them again later.
-It's 100% done.

1831
01:09:14,450 --> 01:09:17,052
-It's okay.
-They think the noodles are done.

1832
01:09:17,119 --> 01:09:19,488
-It's 100% done.
-No, but we'll cook them again later.

1833
01:09:19,555 --> 01:09:20,723
Is it uncooked?

1834
01:09:20,789 --> 01:09:22,491
-It is.
-Yes, she must be nervous,

1835
01:09:22,558 --> 01:09:23,959
but she moves very fast.

1836
01:09:24,026 --> 01:09:25,794
She's moving very fast.

1837
01:09:25,861 --> 01:09:27,696
One of you must make
a big contribution to this dish.

1838
01:09:27,763 --> 01:09:28,964
THAT'S DOUGH…

1839
01:09:29,932 --> 01:09:30,933
She's quick.

1840
01:09:31,000 --> 01:09:32,368
What's that? Sunflower seeds?

1841
01:09:32,434 --> 01:09:34,103
THESE ARE PUMPKIN SEEDS…

1842
01:09:34,170 --> 01:09:35,604
-Pumpkin seeds, I think.
-Pumpkin seeds.

1843
01:09:35,671 --> 01:09:37,239
Pumpkin seed <i>gangjeong</i>.

1844
01:09:37,306 --> 01:09:38,674
PERILLA SEED, PUMPKIN SEED

1845
01:09:38,741 --> 01:09:40,209
He's making <i>gangjeong</i> quickly.

1846
01:09:40,876 --> 01:09:42,745
This is a one-on-three round.

1847
01:09:43,045 --> 01:09:44,847
TO THE FREEZER, GO!

1848
01:09:44,914 --> 01:09:47,550
He puts the <i>gangjeong</i> in the freezer.

1849
01:09:47,616 --> 01:09:49,151
-He must cool them.
-Yes.

1850
01:09:49,218 --> 01:09:50,452
Hurry up!

1851
01:09:50,519 --> 01:09:53,956
-Stir-fry everything together.
-I can't. I have to do them separately.

1852
01:09:54,023 --> 01:09:55,291
Anchovy sauce.

1853
01:09:55,357 --> 01:09:56,792
Wait, it's leaking.

1854
01:09:58,260 --> 01:09:59,195
Was it on purpose?

1855
01:09:59,261 --> 01:10:01,530
See? I told you that would happen
with too much water!

1856
01:10:01,597 --> 01:10:03,432
Didn't I tell you?

1857
01:10:03,499 --> 01:10:04,767
It's our performance.

1858
01:10:05,834 --> 01:10:07,269
Poong was right.

1859
01:10:07,336 --> 01:10:08,337
That's Poong.

1860
01:10:08,404 --> 01:10:10,973
I've failed more than once or twice!

1861
01:10:11,040 --> 01:10:12,708
I'm the poster man of failure!

1862
01:10:12,775 --> 01:10:15,978
-That's Kim Poong.
-You should've listened to the artist!

1863
01:10:16,045 --> 01:10:17,279
-He's right.
-That looks good.

1864
01:10:17,346 --> 01:10:18,447
INTO THE WATER!

1865
01:10:18,514 --> 01:10:19,915
Six minutes and thirty seconds.

1866
01:10:19,982 --> 01:10:22,551
Are you going to just leave
the pressure cooker like that?

1867
01:10:22,618 --> 01:10:24,853
That's not going to fit.

1868
01:10:24,920 --> 01:10:27,656
What is that? What are you doing?

1869
01:10:28,357 --> 01:10:29,191
It's hot.

1870
01:10:29,258 --> 01:10:31,827
The water rarely leaks out
unless there's lots of water.

1871
01:10:31,894 --> 01:10:35,264
-It won't cook. The pressure is gone.
-It'll evaporate anyway.

1872
01:10:35,331 --> 01:10:36,799
There's no pressure inside.

1873
01:10:37,600 --> 01:10:38,734
BEEF JERKY POWDER

1874
01:10:39,702 --> 01:10:40,536
HONEY

1875
01:10:40,603 --> 01:10:43,405
He's making <i>dasik </i>with beef jerky powder.

1876
01:10:43,472 --> 01:10:45,674
-I've never seen it before.
-Beef jerky <i>dasik</i>.

1877
01:10:45,741 --> 01:10:47,810
-Beef jerky <i>dasik</i>.
-The usual beef jerky.

1878
01:10:47,876 --> 01:10:49,245
It'll probably stick to his hands.

1879
01:10:49,311 --> 01:10:52,381
-I've never seen powdered jerky.
-Right?

1880
01:10:52,448 --> 01:10:53,716
It has stopped leaking.

1881
01:10:54,216 --> 01:10:55,718
GETS READY TO SWITCH

1882
01:10:56,318 --> 01:10:57,653
VEGGIE TOPPING 1: ZUCCHINI, CLEARED

1883
01:10:57,720 --> 01:11:00,022
Nam-no is ready to switch with her.

1884
01:11:00,089 --> 01:11:02,758
He's the one who must wrap everything up.

1885
01:11:02,825 --> 01:11:04,893
-Hey.
-You have forty seconds.

1886
01:11:05,694 --> 01:11:06,762
Don't cook them separately.

1887
01:11:06,829 --> 01:11:08,998
-Cook them together.
-We don't have much time.

1888
01:11:09,064 --> 01:11:10,566
I don't think they'll finish in time.

1889
01:11:10,633 --> 01:11:12,301
-They can't.
-They can't.

1890
01:11:12,368 --> 01:11:14,103
I doubt they will finish.

1891
01:11:14,169 --> 01:11:16,639
Chef Jong-won, you won.

1892
01:11:17,373 --> 01:11:18,741
You won.

1893
01:11:18,807 --> 01:11:19,642
Hurry up.

1894
01:11:19,708 --> 01:11:20,843
30 SECONDS UNTIL SWAPPING

1895
01:11:20,909 --> 01:11:22,645
Five minutes left.

1896
01:11:22,711 --> 01:11:24,146
I need one more minute.

1897
01:11:24,213 --> 01:11:25,714
No, I really can't do that.

1898
01:11:25,781 --> 01:11:28,050
-What's your plan?
-Stir-fry and season these.

1899
01:11:28,117 --> 01:11:29,418
Just do it in one pan.

1900
01:11:29,485 --> 01:11:30,619
Why would I do that?

1901
01:11:30,686 --> 01:11:31,920
6. COOK SHIITAKE IN SOY SAUCE, GARLIC

1902
01:11:31,987 --> 01:11:35,524
-Where is it? Blanched perilla leaves.
-What?

1903
01:11:35,591 --> 01:11:37,192
-How would I know?
-It's right here.

1904
01:11:38,427 --> 01:11:39,461
CHWINAMUL & PERILLA LEAVES

1905
01:11:39,528 --> 01:11:42,231
You can use one more minute
and tag out quickly.

1906
01:11:42,298 --> 01:11:44,099
-You have to get the shiitake.
-Hurry!

1907
01:11:44,166 --> 01:11:45,167
7. SEASON WITH SESAME OIL, SALT

1908
01:11:45,401 --> 01:11:47,202
DISTRACTED

1909
01:11:48,304 --> 01:11:49,438
Wow.

1910
01:11:49,505 --> 01:11:51,073
We've seen that before.

1911
01:11:51,140 --> 01:11:52,274
8. PUT BEAN POWDER IN DASIK BOARD

1912
01:11:52,341 --> 01:11:53,876
-A <i>dasik</i> board.
-Yes.

1913
01:11:53,942 --> 01:11:56,312
He'll put bean powder in first,
and the beef jerky powder.

1914
01:11:56,378 --> 01:11:58,514
-On top of that?
-I see.

1915
01:11:58,580 --> 01:12:00,482
-Four minutes and fifty seconds.
-Five minutes!

1916
01:12:00,549 --> 01:12:02,418
Please report from the kitchen, Jung-hwan.

1917
01:12:02,484 --> 01:12:04,887
The young guns have yet to switch.

1918
01:12:04,953 --> 01:12:07,823
-Keep cooking the shiitake!
-Leave it there.

1919
01:12:07,890 --> 01:12:09,925
-Go.
-What are you doing?

1920
01:12:09,992 --> 01:12:10,959
TAG, YOON NAM-NO

1921
01:12:11,026 --> 01:12:12,027
They tagged!

1922
01:12:12,094 --> 01:12:15,164
-Wait a minute. What if it blows up?
-Nam-no.

1923
01:12:15,230 --> 01:12:17,066
Nothing here is finished.

1924
01:12:17,132 --> 01:12:18,434
Everything is going perfectly.

1925
01:12:18,500 --> 01:12:21,270
You only seem distracted.
How will she be inspired by this?

1926
01:12:21,337 --> 01:12:24,873
-Four minutes left.
-Is this the broth?

1927
01:12:24,940 --> 01:12:27,376
-<i>Eobok-jaengban.</i>
-I think it'll explode.

1928
01:12:27,443 --> 01:12:30,813
Pressure cookers cook the food
by giving it pressure inside,

1929
01:12:30,879 --> 01:12:33,949
but you saw the water leaking,
it means there's no pressure in there.

1930
01:12:34,016 --> 01:12:36,418
Hey. I'll kill you if the meat's uncooked.

1931
01:12:36,485 --> 01:12:37,986
It's okay to cook beef to medium.

1932
01:12:38,053 --> 01:12:40,723
NAM-NO'S TO-DO LIST: FINISH BROTH,
YUKJANG, CUT MEAT, GREEN ONION GEOTJEORI

1933
01:12:40,789 --> 01:12:42,591
They don't have much time left.

1934
01:12:42,658 --> 01:12:44,793
Jong-won remains calm.

1935
01:12:45,627 --> 01:12:49,398
He's stuffing the ground beef jerky
into this board.

1936
01:12:49,465 --> 01:12:51,033
-That can inspire her.
-Yes.

1937
01:12:51,100 --> 01:12:53,302
And he's deep-frying these
in low temperature.

1938
01:12:53,369 --> 01:12:55,037
They're done!

1939
01:12:56,338 --> 01:12:58,407
GRAIN SYRUP, GINGER CHEONG,
CINNAMON POWDER

1940
01:12:58,474 --> 01:13:01,443
Those <i>juak</i> look just right.

1941
01:13:01,510 --> 01:13:02,444
Nice line.

1942
01:13:02,778 --> 01:13:03,779
PROUD

1943
01:13:04,113 --> 01:13:06,215
10. COAT FRIED JUAK WITH GRAIN SYRUP

1944
01:13:06,281 --> 01:13:09,651
He's now soaking the <i>juak</i> in the syrup.

1945
01:13:09,718 --> 01:13:11,887
Is the <i>sikhye</i> ready?

1946
01:13:11,954 --> 01:13:13,889
-It's not.
-Even the <i>sikhye</i> isn't ready?

1947
01:13:13,956 --> 01:13:17,659
I don't see anything that's finished yet.
He has been boiling some <i>sikhye</i> here.

1948
01:13:17,726 --> 01:13:19,461
He grabs the <i>gangjeong </i>from the freezer.

1949
01:13:19,528 --> 01:13:21,130
Have they been chilled?

1950
01:13:21,196 --> 01:13:23,298
It seems slanted.

1951
01:13:23,365 --> 01:13:24,266
SHH!

1952
01:13:24,333 --> 01:13:27,136
The pumpkin seeds have slid everywhere.

1953
01:13:28,203 --> 01:13:29,872
Dang it.

1954
01:13:30,439 --> 01:13:31,640
The seeds are everywhere.

1955
01:13:32,040 --> 01:13:33,976
TIDYING UP BEEF JERKY DASIK!

1956
01:13:34,042 --> 01:13:36,545
<i>Gangjeong</i> is also called <i>baksan</i>.

1957
01:13:36,612 --> 01:13:38,280
-Called what?
-<i>Baksan</i>.

1958
01:13:38,347 --> 01:13:40,549
-Like pine nut <i>baksan</i>.
-<i>Baksan</i>.

1959
01:13:40,616 --> 01:13:41,483
Seed <i>baksan</i>.

1960
01:13:41,550 --> 01:13:44,253
-"Seed <i>baksan</i>"?
-Seed <i>baksan</i> has slid sideways.

1961
01:13:44,319 --> 01:13:45,888
-I hope it comes off.
-What does it…

1962
01:13:46,755 --> 01:13:48,023
-I hope it comes off.
-What does it…

1963
01:13:48,090 --> 01:13:49,258
GREATLY SHOCKED

1964
01:13:50,025 --> 01:13:53,128
-This is trouble!
-Did it come off?

1965
01:13:53,195 --> 01:13:54,496
It hasn't hardened yet!

1966
01:13:54,563 --> 01:13:57,633
<i>My job isn't to be flustered.</i>
<i>It's to find a solution.</i>

1967
01:13:57,866 --> 01:13:59,368
WHAT'S HIS SOLUTION?

1968
01:13:59,435 --> 01:14:00,636
TURNING AWAY!

1969
01:14:00,702 --> 01:14:01,703
It's not hardened!

1970
01:14:01,770 --> 01:14:04,373
NOTHING IS WRONG
NOTHING IS WRONG…

1971
01:14:04,440 --> 01:14:05,707
It should've been chilled.

1972
01:14:05,774 --> 01:14:07,109
Put ice on the tray.

1973
01:14:07,176 --> 01:14:08,410
We're doing great.

1974
01:14:08,477 --> 01:14:10,012
-You're doing great.
-That smells good.

1975
01:14:10,078 --> 01:14:11,213
You're doing great now.

1976
01:14:11,280 --> 01:14:12,314
FINISHING THE GREEN ONION FIRST

1977
01:14:12,381 --> 01:14:13,949
It's going according to plan.

1978
01:14:14,016 --> 01:14:15,284
GREEN ONION

1979
01:14:15,984 --> 01:14:18,854
The young guns look busy.
Chef Eun-yeong looks anxious.

1980
01:14:18,921 --> 01:14:20,856
-What are you doing?
-Hurry up.

1981
01:14:20,923 --> 01:14:23,325
-Will Nam-no end this successfully?
-Green onion kimchi.

1982
01:14:23,392 --> 01:14:24,293
Where's the anchovy sauce?

1983
01:14:24,359 --> 01:14:25,461
Anchovy sauce.

1984
01:14:25,527 --> 01:14:26,528
Find the anchovy sauce.

1985
01:14:26,595 --> 01:14:28,730
It's right in front of you.

1986
01:14:29,097 --> 01:14:30,499
SALTED ANCHOVY SAUCE

1987
01:14:30,566 --> 01:14:32,100
8. MIX GREEN ONION WITH CONDIMENTS

1988
01:14:32,167 --> 01:14:34,002
They haven't made anything yet.

1989
01:14:34,069 --> 01:14:36,205
You have two more minutes.

1990
01:14:36,271 --> 01:14:37,272
The green onion dish.

1991
01:14:37,339 --> 01:14:39,241
-Nam-no will take the full blame.
-You got this.

1992
01:14:39,308 --> 01:14:41,310
You have to slice the meat!

1993
01:14:41,643 --> 01:14:43,445
JONG-WON HAD RUN AWAY TO THE JUAK

1994
01:14:43,512 --> 01:14:45,547
You have two more minutes.

1995
01:14:45,848 --> 01:14:47,883
TIME TO FACE REALITY

1996
01:14:47,950 --> 01:14:48,884
Put ice on top…

1997
01:14:48,951 --> 01:14:50,452
-Oh, no.
-Darn it!

1998
01:14:52,154 --> 01:14:54,156
COVER IT FOR NOW!

1999
01:14:56,592 --> 01:14:59,528
SON JONG-WON FACES A HUGE CRISIS!

2000
01:15:03,799 --> 01:15:05,100
He failed!

2001
01:15:05,167 --> 01:15:07,970
-Hey, he failed. Chef Jong-won failed.
-He failed.

2002
01:15:08,036 --> 01:15:09,671
-Just throw them in.
-Just serve it.

2003
01:15:09,738 --> 01:15:11,273
-Serve it, and we win.
-Yes, just serve it.

2004
01:15:11,340 --> 01:15:13,308
The seed <i>baksan</i> has been demolished!

2005
01:15:13,375 --> 01:15:15,344
-It got destroyed!
-It's been destroyed!

2006
01:15:15,410 --> 01:15:17,412
-You can save it.
-It's destroyed!

2007
01:15:17,479 --> 01:15:20,082
-You can open it.
-This is bad.

2008
01:15:20,148 --> 01:15:21,850
THE PRESSURE COOKER WON'T OPEN

2009
01:15:21,917 --> 01:15:23,619
-It hasn't hardened.
-Oh, no.

2010
01:15:23,685 --> 01:15:26,955
Remove the pressure. Yes. Even more.

2011
01:15:27,022 --> 01:15:30,158
IT'D BE NICE IF SOMEONE COULD
KEEP DOING THIS FOR US

2012
01:15:30,225 --> 01:15:31,793
A minute and 40 seconds.

2013
01:15:31,860 --> 01:15:34,162
-It looks like…
-Plate the noodles.

2014
01:15:34,229 --> 01:15:35,330
Wait, look at this!

2015
01:15:35,397 --> 01:15:38,467
Isn't this <i>sikhye?</i> It's boiling too hard!

2016
01:15:38,534 --> 01:15:41,603
-Both sides are in an emergency.
-It's an emergency.

2017
01:15:41,670 --> 01:15:42,771
I can't watch this anymore.

2018
01:15:42,838 --> 01:15:44,273
Something smells burnt.

2019
01:15:44,339 --> 01:15:46,074
He says something smells burnt!

2020
01:15:46,141 --> 01:15:47,576
He's in trouble.

2021
01:15:47,643 --> 01:15:49,111
Seeds are destroyed, and <i>sikhye</i> got burnt.

2022
01:15:49,711 --> 01:15:51,547
And he can't open the lid.

2023
01:15:51,613 --> 01:15:54,550
A minute and 20 seconds!

2024
01:15:54,616 --> 01:15:57,753
It looks like Director Kang
is regretting the decision to be here.

2025
01:15:57,819 --> 01:15:59,855
-Watch your hand!
-"Why did I come here?"

2026
01:16:00,389 --> 01:16:01,423
THE BROTH AND MEAT IS INSIDE!

2027
01:16:01,490 --> 01:16:03,392
-That pot does not explode!
-Okay.

2028
01:16:03,458 --> 01:16:05,394
-Is everything cooked?
-Is it?

2029
01:16:05,460 --> 01:16:07,663
-The broth.
-Season the broth!

2030
01:16:07,729 --> 01:16:09,131
-It's the meat.
-Is the broth seasoned?

2031
01:16:09,197 --> 01:16:11,233
Good call with the chicken stock.

2032
01:16:11,300 --> 01:16:12,434
That's too much.

2033
01:16:12,501 --> 01:16:15,504
-You don't have much time left!
-Try the sauce too!

2034
01:16:15,571 --> 01:16:16,572
-It's good.
-The broth.

2035
01:16:16,638 --> 01:16:18,540
-Just the broth.
-You have under a minute.

2036
01:16:18,607 --> 01:16:21,009
Don't think that it's hot. It's not.

2037
01:16:21,076 --> 01:16:22,311
Just don't think that it's hot.

2038
01:16:22,377 --> 01:16:23,745
You have 30 seconds left.

2039
01:16:24,313 --> 01:16:27,349
It looks perfectly cooked
and absolutely delicious.

2040
01:16:27,749 --> 01:16:29,952
JONG-WON MUST SERVE THE BEEF JERKY DASIK

2041
01:16:30,719 --> 01:16:31,887
TA-DA

2042
01:16:32,521 --> 01:16:33,355
GANGJEONG, READY

2043
01:16:33,889 --> 01:16:34,957
DASIK, READY

2044
01:16:35,023 --> 01:16:36,358
You have fifty seconds left!

2045
01:16:37,426 --> 01:16:39,861
ELEGANT PORCELAIN DISH AND A KETTLE

2046
01:16:40,128 --> 01:16:41,430
WARM YUJA SIKHYE

2047
01:16:43,298 --> 01:16:46,368
-Everything is chaotic.
-He's pouring the <i>sikhye</i>.

2048
01:16:46,435 --> 01:16:48,170
The <i>sikhye</i>… It's <i>yuja sikhye</i>.

2049
01:16:48,236 --> 01:16:49,738
-Jong-won is busy too!
-<i>Yuja sikhye</i>?

2050
01:16:49,805 --> 01:16:52,341
-He's busy too.
-Must've been the <i>yuja</i>. It wasn't burnt.

2051
01:16:52,407 --> 01:16:55,077
-The seed <i>baksan</i> is the problem.
-Yes.

2052
01:16:55,143 --> 01:16:56,411
Fifteen seconds!

2053
01:16:56,478 --> 01:16:58,480
-You have fifteen seconds.
-Fifteen seconds!

2054
01:16:58,547 --> 01:16:59,915
It looks good.

2055
01:16:59,982 --> 01:17:03,251
-Ten seconds. Nine. Eight.
-It has to be good.

2056
01:17:03,318 --> 01:17:05,854
-Seven. Six.
-It's so hot! Damn!

2057
01:17:05,921 --> 01:17:07,689
-Six.
-It's so hot! Damn!

2058
01:17:07,756 --> 01:17:09,391
-Five. Four.
-It isn't hot!

2059
01:17:09,458 --> 01:17:12,227
3. SLICE MEAT, CLEARED
ADD NOODLES

2060
01:17:12,294 --> 01:17:13,261
-One!
-One!

2061
01:17:13,328 --> 01:17:15,197
-Seven. Six.
-Seven. Six.

2062
01:17:15,263 --> 01:17:18,066
ALL GANGJEONG PIECES ARE PLATED SAFELY!

2063
01:17:18,133 --> 01:17:19,801
ONLY 2 GANGJEONG?

2064
01:17:19,868 --> 01:17:21,903
-Two. One.
-Two. One.

2065
01:17:21,970 --> 01:17:25,140
-Time's up.
-You cannot cook anything more.

2066
01:17:25,207 --> 01:17:29,911
You can only serve what you have now.
The young guns are done, then Jong-won.

2067
01:17:29,978 --> 01:17:32,247
-That was so rough.
-The round is over.

2068
01:17:32,314 --> 01:17:33,849
I can't do this.

2069
01:17:34,616 --> 01:17:36,318
You can't add anything new now.

2070
01:17:39,254 --> 01:17:41,923
-Director Kang is here stressing out…
-I'm so stressed out.

2071
01:17:41,990 --> 01:17:43,592
Just watching this stresses me out.

2072
01:17:44,059 --> 01:17:45,794
LEFT A STRONG IMPRESSION

2073
01:17:45,861 --> 01:17:47,829
-It's such a tough rally.
-It's a sporting event.

2074
01:17:47,896 --> 01:17:52,467
FEELING THE THRILL
OF THE 15-MINUTE COOK-OFF

2075
01:17:53,001 --> 01:17:55,771
I don't think I see
everything you were promised.

2076
01:17:57,339 --> 01:18:01,276
And now, everything
has been made for Director Kang.

2077
01:18:01,343 --> 01:18:03,011
That must've been shocking.

2078
01:18:06,181 --> 01:18:09,851
We were overly excited
to have an Oscar winner here with us.

2079
01:18:09,918 --> 01:18:11,386
There's one thing we must share.

2080
01:18:11,453 --> 01:18:13,288
-What is it?
-Our leader will tell you.

2081
01:18:13,355 --> 01:18:16,091
-Eun-yeong is the leader?
-You've decided on who it is now?

2082
01:18:16,158 --> 01:18:18,527
He used another minute,

2083
01:18:18,593 --> 01:18:20,362
-so everything got delayed.
-One minute.

2084
01:18:20,429 --> 01:18:22,998
We wanted to slice some more meat for you,

2085
01:18:23,065 --> 01:18:25,634
so we were wondering if we could do that.

2086
01:18:25,701 --> 01:18:27,502
You need Jong-won's permission.

2087
01:18:27,569 --> 01:18:28,870
CHEF

2088
01:18:29,204 --> 01:18:30,539
PLEASE SAY YES

2089
01:18:30,605 --> 01:18:32,374
So, Chef Jong-won.

2090
01:18:32,441 --> 01:18:33,909
Did you serve everything you had planned?

2091
01:18:33,975 --> 01:18:37,846
I wanted to prepare
three types of <i>gangjeong</i>,

2092
01:18:37,913 --> 01:18:40,115
and while using pumpkin seeds,

2093
01:18:40,182 --> 01:18:42,984
I realized they weren't in season,
and it didn't taste quite perfect.

2094
01:18:43,051 --> 01:18:45,153
So I boldly decided to leave one out.

2095
01:18:45,220 --> 01:18:46,555
It wasn't in season,

2096
01:18:46,621 --> 01:18:48,323
so you didn't fail to make it,
you chose not to.

2097
01:18:48,390 --> 01:18:51,326
I couldn't serve something like that
to my guest.

2098
01:18:51,393 --> 01:18:53,862
Wow. Chef Jong-won has improved.

2099
01:18:53,929 --> 01:18:56,565
HE'S NOW GOT SHAMELESSNESS UNDER HIS BELT

2100
01:18:56,631 --> 01:18:58,333
The perilla seeds looked perfect.

2101
01:18:58,400 --> 01:18:59,468
Not in season excuse is a first.

2102
01:18:59,534 --> 01:19:01,503
Our pork is in season, so may we serve it?

2103
01:19:01,570 --> 01:19:03,305
-Pork in season.
-What's in season?

2104
01:19:03,939 --> 01:19:05,540
Are there good seasons
for pork and chicken?

2105
01:19:05,607 --> 01:19:06,942
-Of course.
-It's in season now.

2106
01:19:07,008 --> 01:19:09,778
They want to add in-season ingredients,
and on the contrary, he's leaving it out.

2107
01:19:09,845 --> 01:19:12,047
Put a hand on your heart
and swear that it's true.

2108
01:19:12,114 --> 01:19:13,548
-It's totally in season.
-Is it?

2109
01:19:13,615 --> 01:19:15,751
-I swear it's totally in season.
-It's in season.

2110
01:19:15,817 --> 01:19:17,986
In that case, I'll give it to them.

2111
01:19:18,053 --> 01:19:19,888
You can add it if it's in season.

2112
01:19:19,955 --> 01:19:21,656
-It's in season.
-If it is.

2113
01:19:21,723 --> 01:19:23,391
Take mine.

2114
01:19:23,458 --> 01:19:25,293
Look at this.

2115
01:19:25,360 --> 01:19:26,561
Fresh, this year's pork and chicken.

2116
01:19:26,628 --> 01:19:27,696
That's not a thing.

2117
01:19:27,763 --> 01:19:30,165
No one says that.

2118
01:19:30,232 --> 01:19:32,768
-I've only heard of newly harvested rice.
-Yes.

2119
01:19:32,834 --> 01:19:34,069
LOTS OF IN-SEASON PORK AND CHICKEN

2120
01:19:34,402 --> 01:19:35,604
SHE'LL BEGIN WITH HURTRIX'S DISH

2121
01:19:35,670 --> 01:19:37,105
Please try the <i>eobok-jaengban</i> first.

2122
01:19:37,706 --> 01:19:41,643
HEARTY TOPPINGS MEET
CLEAN, REFRESHING BROTH

2123
01:19:41,710 --> 01:19:42,544
AND HANDMADE NOODLES

2124
01:19:44,246 --> 01:19:48,350
SUNG-JUN, EUN-YEONG, NAM-NO
I HOPE TO SEE MYSELF IN KDH 2 BY HURTRIX

2125
01:19:48,416 --> 01:19:50,085
Please try the dish first.

2126
01:19:50,152 --> 01:19:51,353
-For <i>KDH 2.</i>
-Yes.

2127
01:19:51,419 --> 01:19:53,789
-She takes a picture first.
-She takes pictures.

2128
01:19:53,855 --> 01:19:55,423
<i>Eobok-jaengban</i>.

2129
01:19:56,091 --> 01:19:58,894
Meat and <i>namul</i>.

2130
01:19:58,960 --> 01:20:00,629
And the broth.

2131
01:20:00,695 --> 01:20:03,331
-You mixed all the meat broth, right?
-Yes.

2132
01:20:03,398 --> 01:20:04,866
I added <i>dongchimi</i> water too.

2133
01:20:04,933 --> 01:20:06,034
-<i>Dongchimi</i>?
-You added that too?

2134
01:20:06,101 --> 01:20:08,403
It's the broth you cooked in the cooker

2135
01:20:08,470 --> 01:20:10,172
-With dongchimi water.
-with <i>dongchimi </i>water?

2136
01:20:10,238 --> 01:20:11,840
That sounds delicious.

2137
01:20:11,907 --> 01:20:14,309
So this isn't just one dish.

2138
01:20:14,376 --> 01:20:16,311
First, please enjoy the soup first.

2139
01:20:16,378 --> 01:20:17,813
First soup, then the noodles.

2140
01:20:17,879 --> 01:20:19,047
Why is he so talkative?

2141
01:20:19,114 --> 01:20:20,949
-Then, the garnish.
-Quiet. Noodles go last.

2142
01:20:21,016 --> 01:20:22,617
Can only one of you speak?

2143
01:20:22,684 --> 01:20:25,487
Only one of you can talk at a time.
It's chaotic.

2144
01:20:26,888 --> 01:20:27,722
Oh.

2145
01:20:29,424 --> 01:20:31,893
-You made the soup, right?
-She's feeling the soup.

2146
01:20:31,960 --> 01:20:32,928
It must be amazing.

2147
01:20:33,395 --> 01:20:35,130
SHE QUIETLY GOES BACK FOR ANOTHER SIP

2148
01:20:35,197 --> 01:20:37,098
Koreans are all about soups.

2149
01:20:37,165 --> 01:20:39,367
-It melts your body.
-It's unique.

2150
01:20:39,434 --> 01:20:42,170
In a positive way? Or a negative way?

2151
01:20:42,237 --> 01:20:44,105
-It's a good thing.
-Good?

2152
01:20:44,372 --> 01:20:45,974
PLEASED

2153
01:20:46,374 --> 01:20:47,609
GOES FOR SOUP FOR THE 3RD TIME

2154
01:20:47,676 --> 01:20:49,778
-She's focused on the soup.
-Do you like the soup?

2155
01:20:49,845 --> 01:20:51,680
-She keeps going back for more.
-Yes, the soup

2156
01:20:51,746 --> 01:20:54,115
-has a bit of sourness to it.
-I'm sure.

2157
01:20:54,182 --> 01:20:56,585
-It's <i>dongchimi</i> water.
-Yes, it's the <i>dongchimi</i>.

2158
01:20:56,651 --> 01:20:58,687
-She likes that bit of sourness.
-It's refreshing.

2159
01:20:58,753 --> 01:21:01,256
I'm sure it's refreshing.
They used <i>dongchimi </i>water.

2160
01:21:02,224 --> 01:21:04,893
They made it like
warm Pyongyang <i>naengmyeon</i>.

2161
01:21:04,960 --> 01:21:06,161
Yes, warm Pyongyang <i>naengmyeon</i>.

2162
01:21:06,228 --> 01:21:08,029
P for positive in parentheses.

2163
01:21:08,096 --> 01:21:11,766
Can this replace <i>seolleongtang</i>?

2164
01:21:12,400 --> 01:21:14,736
If she likes the dish, it may show up

2165
01:21:14,803 --> 01:21:16,705
-instead of <i>seolleongtang</i>.
-The meat is cooked well.

2166
01:21:16,771 --> 01:21:19,407
-The chicken is really tender.
-And?

2167
01:21:19,474 --> 01:21:21,209
Yes, it's soft.

2168
01:21:22,544 --> 01:21:24,446
Yes, it's soft.

2169
01:21:24,512 --> 01:21:25,981
-Now the beef.
-Okay.

2170
01:21:26,882 --> 01:21:28,483
AMAZED AS SOON AS SHE TAKES A BITE

2171
01:21:28,550 --> 01:21:30,619
This beef is really tender.

2172
01:21:30,685 --> 01:21:32,153
-It's really tender.
-Who cooked the meat?

2173
01:21:32,220 --> 01:21:33,555
-Who did it?
-Me.

2174
01:21:33,622 --> 01:21:35,156
No, the pressure cooker.

2175
01:21:35,223 --> 01:21:36,591
It was the pressure cooker.

2176
01:21:36,658 --> 01:21:38,293
Who added that amount of water?

2177
01:21:38,360 --> 01:21:39,895
Is this plain soy sauce?

2178
01:21:39,961 --> 01:21:42,063
It's <i>yukjang</i>, a dip for meat.

2179
01:21:42,130 --> 01:21:43,398
It looks so good.

2180
01:21:43,465 --> 01:21:44,699
That looks good too.

2181
01:21:46,902 --> 01:21:47,936
The meat must be good.

2182
01:21:48,003 --> 01:21:49,437
There's a hint of sweetness.

2183
01:21:49,704 --> 01:21:51,206
WILL YUKJANG GET A PASS TOO?

2184
01:21:51,606 --> 01:21:53,575
SHE TRIES THE DIP ONE MORE TIME

2185
01:21:53,642 --> 01:21:55,510
-It's easy to chew.
-Yes.

2186
01:21:55,577 --> 01:21:57,245
-It's cooked well.
-Very much.

2187
01:21:57,312 --> 01:21:59,447
-Is it just sweet?
-No.

2188
01:21:59,514 --> 01:22:02,017
-It's on the sweeter side. It's sweet.
-The sauce is sweet?

2189
01:22:02,584 --> 01:22:03,919
I told you to skip the starch syrup.

2190
01:22:03,985 --> 01:22:06,187
-I told you to stop adding it.
-I said I didn't want it.

2191
01:22:06,488 --> 01:22:07,689
SPEECHLESS

2192
01:22:07,756 --> 01:22:09,357
Is it adequately sweet or too sweet?

2193
01:22:09,424 --> 01:22:12,594
-It's not sweet in a bad way.
-Not in a bad way.

2194
01:22:12,661 --> 01:22:14,162
Another P for positive.

2195
01:22:14,729 --> 01:22:17,766
It's a different experience
when you eat it with the sauce.

2196
01:22:17,832 --> 01:22:19,935
-A new experience.
-Yes, a new experience.

2197
01:22:20,001 --> 01:22:21,703
-Is this pork?
-Is it?

2198
01:22:21,770 --> 01:22:23,705
-That's pork.
-That's really good too.

2199
01:22:24,272 --> 01:22:25,807
They used beef, chicken, and pork.

2200
01:22:25,874 --> 01:22:26,708
Mmm.

2201
01:22:26,775 --> 01:22:28,143
-Isn't it amazing?
-It is.

2202
01:22:28,209 --> 01:22:30,278
-Will you be quiet? She's trying to eat.
-I'm sorry.

2203
01:22:30,345 --> 01:22:31,579
-She just needs to like one thing.
-The topping.

2204
01:22:31,646 --> 01:22:32,714
The soup and meat passed.

2205
01:22:32,781 --> 01:22:35,717
-I think <i>namul </i>is the culprit.
-No, the <i>namul</i> is perfect.

2206
01:22:35,784 --> 01:22:38,787
She's imagining the film in her head
as she eats,

2207
01:22:38,853 --> 01:22:40,188
so she's very serious.

2208
01:22:41,056 --> 01:22:43,992
She's thinking,
"Will <i>eobok-jaengban </i>make it into<i> KDH 2</i>?"

2209
01:22:44,059 --> 01:22:46,461
What happened to the noodles?
Is it made of konjac?

2210
01:22:46,528 --> 01:22:47,529
Is it konjac?

2211
01:22:49,164 --> 01:22:50,165
What's it like?

2212
01:22:50,498 --> 01:22:52,100
WHAT ARE THE FRESH NOODLES LIKE?

2213
01:22:52,167 --> 01:22:53,668
They're quite different

2214
01:22:53,735 --> 01:22:55,837
-from the ones I had earlier.
-Really?

2215
01:22:55,904 --> 01:22:58,807
They're different from Sam's noodles?

2216
01:22:58,873 --> 01:23:01,142
Those noodles were really chewy,

2217
01:23:01,209 --> 01:23:02,844
but these are a bit…

2218
01:23:03,545 --> 01:23:05,146
They aren't chewy.

2219
01:23:05,213 --> 01:23:06,681
N for negative.

2220
01:23:06,748 --> 01:23:08,883
Would you have preferred them to be chewy?

2221
01:23:08,950 --> 01:23:12,754
They would've been better
if they were a little chewier.

2222
01:23:12,821 --> 01:23:14,122
Who cooked the noodles?

2223
01:23:14,189 --> 01:23:16,224
He made the dough.

2224
01:23:16,558 --> 01:23:18,860
THE WORST TEAMWORK

2225
01:23:18,927 --> 01:23:21,096
They go after each other
in times like these.

2226
01:23:21,162 --> 01:23:23,264
He did say the dough was dry.

2227
01:23:23,331 --> 01:23:26,234
-You must like the soup a lot.
-Yes, it's quite unique.

2228
01:23:26,301 --> 01:23:27,702
She's sipping on the soup a lot.

2229
01:23:28,870 --> 01:23:30,805
I've never had anything like this before.

2230
01:23:30,872 --> 01:23:34,676
The <i>seolleongtang </i>scene
was a huge hit in <i>KDH</i>.

2231
01:23:34,743 --> 01:23:38,313
Will <i>eobok-jaengban</i>
be able to replace that?

2232
01:23:38,380 --> 01:23:39,447
That's a possibility.

2233
01:23:40,815 --> 01:23:42,650
She said it in a cold tone.

2234
01:23:42,917 --> 01:23:44,519
BOO…

2235
01:23:44,586 --> 01:23:46,187
"That's a possibility." Like that.

2236
01:23:46,254 --> 01:23:47,455
It sounded a bit cold.

2237
01:23:47,522 --> 01:23:49,224
-"Maybe not."
-Right.

2238
01:23:49,290 --> 01:23:52,093
All right, then. Chef Jong-won's dish.

2239
01:23:52,160 --> 01:23:55,096
Is This Hangwa Worthy of <i>KDH 2</i>?

2240
01:23:55,163 --> 01:23:56,965
3 K-SNACKS FOR THE WORLD TO FIND OUT

2241
01:23:57,565 --> 01:23:59,401
SUNFLOWER SEED GANGJEONG,
PERILLA SEED GANGJEONG

2242
01:23:59,634 --> 01:24:03,738
CHEF SON JONG-WON'S
IS THIS HANGWA WORTHY OF KDH 2?

2243
01:24:03,805 --> 01:24:05,273
First, <i>sikhye</i>.

2244
01:24:05,340 --> 01:24:06,674
Should I pour it?

2245
01:24:06,741 --> 01:24:08,810
Yes, shake it well
and pour the <i>sikhye</i> first.

2246
01:24:08,877 --> 01:24:11,546
-After shaking it.
-There's <i>sikhye</i> in that teapot.

2247
01:24:11,613 --> 01:24:13,882
-Don't spin it three times.
-Right.

2248
01:24:13,948 --> 01:24:15,316
I'm sorry. I didn't realize it.

2249
01:24:15,383 --> 01:24:16,484
You almost had to bow to her.

2250
01:24:16,551 --> 01:24:19,020
HE'S ONLY MIXING SIKHYE

2251
01:24:19,087 --> 01:24:21,356
-Is this warm <i>sikhye</i>?
-It seems warm.

2252
01:24:21,423 --> 01:24:24,092
Most people think
you only drink <i>sikhye</i> cold,

2253
01:24:24,159 --> 01:24:26,327
but it's also enjoyed warm.

2254
01:24:26,394 --> 01:24:29,330
-I've never had warm <i>sikhye</i>.
-It's her first time.

2255
01:24:29,397 --> 01:24:30,465
A cup of <i>sikhye</i>.

2256
01:24:31,266 --> 01:24:33,701
-There's <i>yuja cheong</i> in it.
-It smells like <i>yuja</i>.

2257
01:24:33,768 --> 01:24:35,770
-<i>Yuja</i>'s great.
-Yes, it smells like it.

2258
01:24:35,837 --> 01:24:38,373
It's probably different
from the usual <i>sikhye</i> you've had.

2259
01:24:38,440 --> 01:24:39,307
Warm <i>sikhye</i>.

2260
01:24:39,374 --> 01:24:40,308
I like it.

2261
01:24:42,043 --> 01:24:44,512
First, you can taste the <i>yuja</i>.

2262
01:24:44,579 --> 01:24:47,615
It's then followed by the taste of <i>sikhye</i>.

2263
01:24:47,682 --> 01:24:49,050
-It's new.
-New?

2264
01:24:49,117 --> 01:24:51,586
I've also never seen warm <i>sikhye</i>.

2265
01:24:51,653 --> 01:24:53,388
What should she start with?

2266
01:24:53,455 --> 01:24:55,557
First, please try the <i>juak</i> in the middle.

2267
01:24:55,623 --> 01:24:57,759
It's only made of sticky rice,

2268
01:24:57,826 --> 01:24:58,927
so it has a chewy texture.

2269
01:24:58,993 --> 01:25:02,764
-Younger people these days love that.
-It's trendy.

2270
01:25:02,831 --> 01:25:05,800
They'd eat it with ice cream on top,
and that goes very nicely too.

2271
01:25:05,867 --> 01:25:07,936
-That sounds good.
-I see.

2272
01:25:08,002 --> 01:25:09,104
He put lots of work into it.

2273
01:25:09,170 --> 01:25:10,338
It looks so pretty.

2274
01:25:11,706 --> 01:25:16,010
-He used a precision scale to weigh it.
-Right.

2275
01:25:16,077 --> 01:25:17,679
That's what she's having now.

2276
01:25:18,546 --> 01:25:20,081
-Gaeseong <i>juak</i>.
-<i>Juak</i>.

2277
01:25:20,915 --> 01:25:21,749
Wow.

2278
01:25:21,816 --> 01:25:25,019
It's chewy,
yet it has a crispy bite to it.

2279
01:25:25,086 --> 01:25:26,287
CHEWY YET CRISPY

2280
01:25:26,354 --> 01:25:27,922
It's not too sweet, either.

2281
01:25:29,157 --> 01:25:32,026
In the old days, <i>yangban</i>, the aristocrats,
used to enjoy <i>juak</i>

2282
01:25:32,093 --> 01:25:35,497
<i>as soon as they pulled it out</i>
<i>from the syrup after frying them in oil.</i>

2283
01:25:35,563 --> 01:25:37,132
I prepared it in the traditional way.

2284
01:25:37,198 --> 01:25:39,701
Wasn't our dish, <i>eobok-jaengban</i>,
served to kings?

2285
01:25:39,767 --> 01:25:42,170
-Next, beef jerky <i>dasik</i>.
-Beef jerky <i>dasik</i>.

2286
01:25:42,237 --> 01:25:43,805
This is so new.

2287
01:25:43,872 --> 01:25:45,473
He ground beef jerky.

2288
01:25:45,540 --> 01:25:47,308
BEEF JERKY DASIK SOUNDS UNFAMILIAR

2289
01:25:50,678 --> 01:25:52,080
SHE CHUCKLES SOON AFTER A BITE?

2290
01:25:52,147 --> 01:25:53,948
-It must make her smile.
-She's smiling.

2291
01:25:54,015 --> 01:25:56,885
-She smiled a little.
-That was the first one.

2292
01:25:56,951 --> 01:26:00,121
-Does it taste funny?
-I've never had anything like this.

2293
01:26:00,188 --> 01:26:01,789
What do you mean by that?

2294
01:26:01,856 --> 01:26:03,858
It breaks down into smaller pieces,

2295
01:26:04,726 --> 01:26:06,127
and it has a unique taste.

2296
01:26:06,327 --> 01:26:07,595
THAT MEANS

2297
01:26:08,830 --> 01:26:10,832
-Is it a good sign for us?
-I don't know.

2298
01:26:11,099 --> 01:26:12,600
WHAT'S WITH THEM?

2299
01:26:12,667 --> 01:26:16,137
I can't really taste the beef jerky.

2300
01:26:16,204 --> 01:26:17,672
You mixed it with something.

2301
01:26:17,739 --> 01:26:21,743
<i>I mixed it with honey,</i>
<i>then served it with bean powder.</i>

2302
01:26:21,809 --> 01:26:24,112
I never knew beef jerky

2303
01:26:24,179 --> 01:26:26,481
could taste like this.

2304
01:26:27,048 --> 01:26:28,216
Next, the perilla seed <i>gangjeong</i>.

2305
01:26:28,283 --> 01:26:29,317
Perilla seed <i>gangjeong</i>.

2306
01:26:30,852 --> 01:26:32,520
IN ONE BITE

2307
01:26:33,655 --> 01:26:36,791
I hope it doesn't get stuck on your teeth.

2308
01:26:36,858 --> 01:26:39,127
-It's not like that at all.
-Not at all?

2309
01:26:39,194 --> 01:26:42,363
It's not too hard, so it's easy to eat.

2310
01:26:42,430 --> 01:26:44,699
-The last one, sunflower seeds.
-Sunflower seeds.

2311
01:26:44,766 --> 01:26:46,067
In-season sunflower seeds.

2312
01:26:47,835 --> 01:26:50,004
He dropped the pumpkin seeds
because they weren't in season.

2313
01:26:50,572 --> 01:26:53,074
You should wash it down with <i>yuja sikhye</i>.

2314
01:26:57,579 --> 01:26:59,380
These are good.

2315
01:26:59,447 --> 01:27:04,052
Chef Jong-won thought it would be nice
if you could use these for a scene

2316
01:27:04,118 --> 01:27:06,754
where the members get together and chat.

2317
01:27:06,821 --> 01:27:07,755
In a <i>hanok</i> house.

2318
01:27:07,822 --> 01:27:10,558
These are very luxurious desserts.

2319
01:27:11,659 --> 01:27:12,660
All right, then.

2320
01:27:12,727 --> 01:27:15,797
-Leejung.
-Please try the <i>eobok-jaengban</i>.

2321
01:27:15,863 --> 01:27:16,698
Mmm.

2322
01:27:16,764 --> 01:27:18,066
CHUCKLING

2323
01:27:18,132 --> 01:27:19,334
It must be good.

2324
01:27:19,400 --> 01:27:23,705
I completely understand
why Director Kang said

2325
01:27:23,771 --> 01:27:25,840
-it's nothing like she had before.
-Right?

2326
01:27:25,907 --> 01:27:29,143
It's sour, but it doesn't taste repulsive.

2327
01:27:29,210 --> 01:27:31,079
I've never had anything like it,
but it's good.

2328
01:27:31,145 --> 01:27:32,947
Try the meat.

2329
01:27:33,014 --> 01:27:35,350
She can eat it with green onion, right?

2330
01:27:35,416 --> 01:27:36,985
-The beef was amazing.
-It seemed so.

2331
01:27:37,785 --> 01:27:39,887
Mmm.

2332
01:27:40,121 --> 01:27:40,989
PROUD

2333
01:27:41,055 --> 01:27:41,889
That's it.

2334
01:27:41,956 --> 01:27:44,158
-It's so good.
-You make it look so good.

2335
01:27:44,225 --> 01:27:45,960
You really do.

2336
01:27:46,027 --> 01:27:48,329
This is really good too.

2337
01:27:48,930 --> 01:27:50,665
I made that.

2338
01:27:51,699 --> 01:27:53,735
-What's the best part?
-It's so good.

2339
01:27:53,801 --> 01:27:54,969
CONFIDENT, ANXIOUS, PROUD

2340
01:27:55,036 --> 01:27:57,472
-He wants to know what the best part is.
-Which one?

2341
01:27:57,538 --> 01:27:59,407
But I really love the zucchini.

2342
01:27:59,474 --> 01:28:02,744
It's not easy to cook <i>namul</i> perfectly.

2343
01:28:02,810 --> 01:28:04,679
-The zucchini was Eun-yeong.
-Yes.

2344
01:28:04,746 --> 01:28:08,016
The result seems too good
compared to their process.

2345
01:28:08,082 --> 01:28:10,785
She's not looking to move on
to the desserts.

2346
01:28:11,819 --> 01:28:13,121
Thank you. It was so good.

2347
01:28:13,388 --> 01:28:14,489
CLEANED OUT

2348
01:28:14,555 --> 01:28:16,758
That was the main dish,

2349
01:28:16,824 --> 01:28:18,860
so please try Chef Jong-won's dessert,

2350
01:28:18,926 --> 01:28:20,628
a <i>hangwa </i>dish.

2351
01:28:21,496 --> 01:28:22,797
Whoa.

2352
01:28:22,864 --> 01:28:23,998
GASPS

2353
01:28:24,065 --> 01:28:24,899
IT TASTES AMAZING!

2354
01:28:24,966 --> 01:28:26,234
Is it different from when it's cold?

2355
01:28:26,301 --> 01:28:29,570
It feels much less thicker than <i>yuja </i>tea,

2356
01:28:29,637 --> 01:28:31,339
and it has a clean aftertaste.

2357
01:28:32,807 --> 01:28:33,775
Gaeseong <i>juak</i>.

2358
01:28:33,841 --> 01:28:35,376
TRIES THE JUAK AND GANGJEONG TOO

2359
01:28:35,443 --> 01:28:37,145
Next, <i>gangjeong</i>.

2360
01:28:39,247 --> 01:28:40,548
This is really good.

2361
01:28:42,417 --> 01:28:43,785
-This is bad.
-She smiled.

2362
01:28:43,851 --> 01:28:45,153
-She really means it.
-What now?

2363
01:28:45,219 --> 01:28:47,322
I keep eating sweets,

2364
01:28:47,388 --> 01:28:50,925
but it has the perfect amount of sweetness
so that I never get sick of it,

2365
01:28:50,992 --> 01:28:52,694
and the size is perfect too.

2366
01:28:53,428 --> 01:28:56,164
-This is really good.
-I see. Very well.

2367
01:28:56,230 --> 01:28:59,100
And now, you must make your choice.

2368
01:28:59,167 --> 01:29:01,736
Which side will Director Kang pick?

2369
01:29:01,803 --> 01:29:03,471
Director Maggie Kang.

2370
01:29:03,538 --> 01:29:05,673
-Yes?
-<i>Eobok-jaengban</i> is a dish

2371
01:29:05,740 --> 01:29:07,675
that bids good luck
and brings in good luck

2372
01:29:07,742 --> 01:29:09,711
when you eat it.

2373
01:29:09,777 --> 01:29:12,246
So we made that dish
hoping to give you more luck

2374
01:29:12,313 --> 01:29:14,482
after hearing that you'll be making <i>KDH 2</i>.

2375
01:29:14,916 --> 01:29:17,218
THANK YOU FOR YOUR BLESSINGS

2376
01:29:17,285 --> 01:29:18,119
Let's do it again.

2377
01:29:18,186 --> 01:29:19,387
GIVING HEARTS TO GET STARS

2378
01:29:21,322 --> 01:29:24,392
<i>Press one for Chef Son Jong-won</i>

2379
01:29:24,459 --> 01:29:25,927
<i>and two for Hurtrix.</i>

2380
01:29:27,362 --> 01:29:30,598
Please make your decision
and push the button!

2381
01:29:31,366 --> 01:29:33,000
This is so hard.

2382
01:29:33,067 --> 01:29:34,569
Let's go, <i>KDH 2</i>!

2383
01:29:34,635 --> 01:29:38,139
-Those three keep giving out hearts.
-I love you, <i>KDH</i>.

2384
01:29:40,108 --> 01:29:42,276
-That's too much pressure.
-It is a lot of pressure.

2385
01:29:42,343 --> 01:29:44,011
-Did you choose one? All right.
-Yes.

2386
01:29:44,078 --> 01:29:46,748
Which side did Director Maggie choose?

2387
01:29:46,814 --> 01:29:48,583
Let's find out the result.

2388
01:29:48,649 --> 01:29:49,550
Show us.

2389
01:29:49,617 --> 01:29:53,054
K-Food Inspo for <i>KDH 2</i>.

2390
01:29:53,121 --> 01:29:56,290
Will it be Hurtrix,
made of Nam-no, Eun-yeong, and Sung-jun?

2391
01:29:56,357 --> 01:29:59,227
Or will it be Chef Jong-won?

2392
01:29:59,293 --> 01:30:01,129
Who did Director Maggie Kang choose?

2393
01:30:01,195 --> 01:30:02,563
Which team is it?

2394
01:30:02,630 --> 01:30:05,299
Which team inspired you more?

2395
01:30:05,366 --> 01:30:06,200
Who won?

2396
01:30:07,268 --> 01:30:08,102
Who won?

2397
01:30:09,604 --> 01:30:11,606
SON JONG-WON WINS

2398
01:30:11,906 --> 01:30:13,007
IS THIS HANGWA WORTHY OF KDH 2? WINS

2399
01:30:13,074 --> 01:30:15,176
Son Jong-won wins!

2400
01:30:15,243 --> 01:30:17,612
-What did I say?
-I'm never teaming up with you two.

2401
01:30:17,678 --> 01:30:20,081
-Go away, you.
-What about the noodles?

2402
01:30:20,148 --> 01:30:22,250
ENDS WITH A BRAWL

2403
01:30:22,316 --> 01:30:23,484
They're in a fight.

2404
01:30:24,285 --> 01:30:25,353
They're fighting.

2405
01:30:26,354 --> 01:30:28,289
-I'm never working with you two.
-Hey.

2406
01:30:28,356 --> 01:30:30,525
I told you not to add that starch syrup.

2407
01:30:30,591 --> 01:30:33,227
-I wanted to be on this team.
-Who uses starch syrup in <i>yukjang</i>?

2408
01:30:33,294 --> 01:30:35,430
What are we going to do with them?

2409
01:30:35,496 --> 01:30:38,099
You must've liked the desserts
more than the <i>eobok-jaengban.</i>

2410
01:30:38,166 --> 01:30:39,000
I could've won alone.

2411
01:30:39,066 --> 01:30:43,037
The moment Chef Jong-won
mentioned the word <i>hangwa</i>,

2412
01:30:43,104 --> 01:30:45,740
I knew it would look beautiful.

2413
01:30:45,807 --> 01:30:50,111
I could imagine what it would look like
if it were animated.

2414
01:30:50,178 --> 01:30:53,080
On top of that,
despite not being a dessert person,

2415
01:30:53,147 --> 01:30:55,817
I loved his dish so much.

2416
01:30:56,017 --> 01:30:57,018
AGREED

2417
01:30:57,084 --> 01:30:58,986
-That was the reason.
-I see.

2418
01:30:59,053 --> 01:31:01,823
Please put a star on Chef Jong-won!

2419
01:31:01,889 --> 01:31:03,224
MAGGIE KANG'S STAR GOES TO JONG-WON

2420
01:31:03,291 --> 01:31:05,660
This means Jong-won becomes
the sole first place once again.

2421
01:31:05,827 --> 01:31:06,661
SOLELY IN 2ND PLACE

2422
01:31:06,727 --> 01:31:09,664
He gets his sixth star
from Director Maggie Kang!

2423
01:31:09,730 --> 01:31:11,799
-Congratulations, Jong-won!
-Thank you.

2424
01:31:11,866 --> 01:31:13,801
-Give us one each.
-Then we'll all have two.

2425
01:31:13,868 --> 01:31:14,902
STAY TUNED FOR THE PREVIEW

2426
01:31:15,169 --> 01:31:16,804
Please welcome today's fridge owners,

2427
01:31:16,871 --> 01:31:18,506
Go Soo and Lee Jong-hyuk!

2428
01:31:18,573 --> 01:31:20,341
I felt my heart race to see him up close.

2429
01:31:20,408 --> 01:31:22,310
He's GoVid,
who outshines Michelangelo's David.

2430
01:31:22,376 --> 01:31:24,045
How does a person look that good?

2431
01:31:24,245 --> 01:31:25,279
HIS UNCHANGING APPEARANCE

2432
01:31:25,346 --> 01:31:26,681
It feels like a dream.

2433
01:31:26,747 --> 01:31:28,216
Why am I so excited?

2434
01:31:28,449 --> 01:31:29,484
EXCITED TO BE ON A VARIETY SHOW

2435
01:31:29,550 --> 01:31:31,085
The cameras are all hidden.

2436
01:31:31,152 --> 01:31:33,421
If you're having fun,
why haven't you done more shows?

2437
01:31:33,488 --> 01:31:34,655
It expired in 2025.

2438
01:31:34,722 --> 01:31:35,923
You can consume some things

2439
01:31:35,990 --> 01:31:37,425
even after the expiration date.

2440
01:31:37,492 --> 01:31:38,759
What do you mean?

2441
01:31:38,826 --> 01:31:39,827
I love ice cream.

2442
01:31:39,894 --> 01:31:40,928
But you're on a strict diet.

2443
01:31:40,995 --> 01:31:43,431
Don't snacks fly off your body instantly?

2444
01:31:43,498 --> 01:31:44,599
Fly off to where?

2445
01:31:44,665 --> 01:31:46,000
NO?

2446
01:31:46,067 --> 01:31:49,203
This is a battle just for Go Soo
between two master chefs.

2447
01:31:49,270 --> 01:31:50,705
THE SHOW-OFF MASTERS' MIRROR MATCH

2448
01:31:50,771 --> 01:31:51,973
Wasn't his arm too short?

2449
01:31:53,140 --> 01:31:54,242
That's too much!

2450
01:31:54,308 --> 01:31:55,643
It's for me.

2451
01:31:55,710 --> 01:31:57,278
Why did you grab so much? Come on.

2452
01:31:57,345 --> 01:31:58,479
SLURP

2453
01:31:58,546 --> 01:31:59,914
THE MASTER MUKBANGER

2454
01:31:59,981 --> 01:32:01,249
He went back for another bite.

2455
01:32:01,315 --> 01:32:02,750
So? What does it taste like?

2456
01:32:02,817 --> 01:32:03,784
Do you want to know?

2457
01:32:03,851 --> 01:32:05,086
Of course, we do.

2458
01:32:06,420 --> 01:32:08,890
-You must be dying to know.
-Yes, we are.

2459
01:32:08,956 --> 01:32:10,758
You've probably never had
anything like this.

2460
01:32:10,825 --> 01:32:11,926
Of course not.

2461
01:32:13,027 --> 01:32:14,695
He keeps leaving us curious.

2462
01:32:14,762 --> 01:32:16,531
He's so good at teasing us.

2463
01:32:18,866 --> 01:32:20,268
I almost paid him 500 won.

2464
01:32:20,334 --> 01:32:21,903
GOT TOO CURIOUS
AND ALMOST PAID HIM FOR AN ANSWER…

2465
01:32:31,812 --> 01:32:36,584
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
